7}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"1\" |''Keith and The Girl''\n|Episode: \"2147: Gang Dick\"<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.keithandthegirl.com/Show-Detail/3722/Gang-Dick.aspx|title=Gang Dick (Keith and The Girl)|publisher=Keith and The Girl|date=March 16, 2015 |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Gilmore Guys]]''\n|Episode 4.21\n|-\n| ''That's the Show with Danny''\n|Episode: \"117: The One with Mara Wilson\"<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.keithandthegirl.com/vip/bonus/episode/9/117/the-one-with-mara-wilson |title=The One with Mara Wilson (That's the Show with Danny)|publisher=That's the Show with Danny |date=March 19, 2015 |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''I Don't Even Own a Television''\n|Episode: \"026: Treacherous Love (w/ Mara Wilson)\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.idontevenownatelevision.com/2015/02/25/treacherous-love-w-mara-wilson/|title=026 \u2014 Treacherous Love (w/ Mara Wilson)|date=February 25, 2015|work=i don't even own a television|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n|''Mouth Time with Reductress''\n|Ruth Hrorgen\n|Mouth Time LIVE! With Mara Wilson<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://reductress.com/post/mouth-time-live-with-mara-wilson/ |title=Episode: \"Mouth Time LIVE! With Mara Wilson\"|publisher=Mouth Time with Reductress |date=June 1, 2016 |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|''I Don't Even Own a Television''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"081: I'm With the Band (w/ Mara Wilson)\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.idontevenownatelevision.com/2017/05/14/081-im-with-the-band-w-mara-wilson/|title=081 \u2014 I'm with the Band (w/ Mara Wilson)|date=May 14, 2017|work=i don't even own a television|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Passenger List''\n|Writer\n|Episode 5: Cyberspace \n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Mara Wilson award nominations\n!Year\n!Organization\n!Award\n!Work\n!Result\n|-\n|1995\n|[[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest Award]]\n|Young Star of the Year\n|N/A\n|Won<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/legit/markets-festivals/unconventional-kudos-nab-stars-1117939714/|title=Unconventional kudos nab stars|author=Joshua L. Weinstein|work=Variety}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Stage==\n* ''Cinderella'' (2005)\n* ''Weren't You That Girl?'' (2009)\n* ''What Are You Afraid Of?'' (2014)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Sheeple'' (2013)\n* ''Where Am I Now?: True Stories of Girlhood and Accidental Fame'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0933798}}\n* [http://mara.substack.com/ Mara Wilson] at Substack\n* [http://www.tv.com/m/people/mara-wilson/ Mara Wilson] at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson, Mara}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual actresses]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Jewish atheists]]\n[[Category:Jewish women writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:People with obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]]\n[[Category:People with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]]\n[[Category:Singers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Burbank, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer and actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mara Wilson\n| image        = Mara Wilson by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = Wilson in November 2017\n| birth_name   = Mara Elizabeth Wilson\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1987|7|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Burbank, California]], U.S.\n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   = [[New York University]]\n| occupation   = Actress, writer\n| years_active = 1993\u20132000; 2012\u2013present\n| relatives    = [[Ben Shapiro]] (cousin)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktth.com/2014/01/24/justin-bieber-symptom-big-problem/|title=Justin Bieber a symptom of a big problem|first=Neal|last=McNamara|publisher=KTTH|date=January 24, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2017|archivedate=July 3, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703191405/http://www.ktth.com/2014/01/24/justin-bieber-symptom-big-problem/}}</ref>\n| website      = [http://marawilsonwritesstuff.com/ Mara Wilson Writes Stuff]\n}}\n\n'''Mara Elizabeth Wilson''' (born July 24, 1987) is an American actress and writer. As a child, she gained prominence playing Natalie Hillard in ''[[Mrs. Doubtfire]]'' (1993), having only appeared in commercials previously. She also played Susan Walker in ''[[Miracle on 34th Street (1994 film)|Miracle on 34th Street]]'' (1994), [[Matilda Wormwood]] in ''[[Matilda (1996 film)|Matilda]]'' (1996), and Lily Stone in ''[[Thomas and the Magic Railroad]]'' (2000). Since retiring from acting in 2000, Wilson has focused on writing and has appeared in numerous [[podcast]]s.\n\n==Early life==\nWilson was born in [[Burbank, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-mara-wilson-20160907-snap-story.html|title=Actress Mara Wilson has a memoir. She's not Matilda anymore.|last=Kaufman|first=Amy|date=September 15, 2016|website=Los Angeles Times|publisher=|access-date=October 4, 2016}}</ref> She is the oldest daughter of Mike Wilson, a television broadcast engineer at KTLA 5 News and Suzie Wilson (n\u00e9e Shapiro; 1953\u20131996), a homemaker and Burbank PTA school volunteer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/SUZIE+WILSON%2C+BURBANK+SCHOOLS%2C+PTA+VOLUNTEER.-a083960287|title=SUZIE WILSON, BURBANK SCHOOLS, PTA VOLUNTEER. <!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> Wilson's mother was Jewish, and her father is of half-Irish descent.<ref>{{cite tweet |author=  |user= MaraWritesStuff|number= 206803935321792514 |date= May 27, 2012 |title= I'm half Jewish and a quarter Irish. I BURN. RT @Pixiebybirth Do you burn, tan or none of ze above? |access-date=  }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=  |user= MaraWritesStuff|number= 165321003210252290 |date= February 2, 2012 |title= @rare_basement He is short, half-Jewish, dark-haired, acted in an adaptation of a British kids' book and has a nickel allergy. HE IS ME. |access-date=  }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|DVp0IFhEQEg|Mara Wilson Interview Pt. 2 \u2014 Running Late with Scott Rogowsky}}</ref> She was raised Jewish<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1717915/mrs-doubtfire-mara-wilson-20th-anniversary-interview/|title=She's His G\u2013damn Kid Too: Mara Wilson On 'Mrs. Doubtfire' 20th Anniversary|work=MTV News}}</ref> and became an [[atheism|atheist]] when she was 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/08-2013/atheism-911-conspiracy-theories-and-sheeple-with-m_65708.html|title=Atheism, 9/11 Conspiracy Theories, and Sheeple with Mara Wilson and Max Reuben|author=Zachary Stewart|date=August 7, 2013|publisher=TheaterMania.com}}</ref> She has three older brothers, Danny, Jon and Joel and a one younger sister, Anna.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-07-26/entertainment/ca-19883_1_mara-wilson|title=To Her, It's Kids' Stuff : Movies: Mara Wilson, 7, is earning praise from her co-stars in the upcoming 'Miracle on 34th Street,' but acting is just something she says she likes--for now.|first=HOWELL J. MALHAM|last=Jr|date=July 26, 1994|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref> Her mother was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]] on March 10, 1995,<ref name=people-cancer>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20141113,00.html|title=Lessons in Courage|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=April 29, 1996 |volume=45 |issue = 17 |first=Gregory|last= Cerio | accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref> and died on April 26, 1996. The film ''Matilda'' was dedicated to her memory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/matilda-star-devito-and-perlman-helped-me-when-mum-lost-cancer-battle_3701309|title=Mara Wilson - Matilda Star: 'Danny Devito And Perlman Helped Me When Mum Lost Cancer Battle'|agency=[[World Entertainment News Network|WENN]]|publisher= ContactMusic.com|date=June 4, 2013}}</ref> Wilson later recalled that this affected her passion for acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/why-hollywood-didnt-want-the-child-star-of-matilda-mara-wilson/story-e6frfmvr-1226775243437|title=Why Hollywood didn't want the child star of Matilda, Mara Wilson|work=NewsComAu}}</ref>\n\nWilson attended [[Idyllwild Arts Academy]] near [[Palm Springs, California]]. After graduation in 2005, Wilson relocated to New York City, where she continued her studies at [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]]. She graduated in 2009.<ref>Ghert-Zand, Renee (April 18, 2012). [http://forward.com/the-assimilator/154979/mara-wilson-hated-being-a-movie-star/ \"Mara Wilson Hated Being a Movie Star\"]. ''[[The Forward]]''.</ref> While at New York University she appeared in her own one-woman show called ''Weren't You That Girl?''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyulocal.com/on-campus/2009/01/19/mara-wilson-on-child-stardom-morons-wanting-to-party-with-matilda/|title=Mara Wilson On Child Stardom, Morons Wanting to \"Party With Matilda\" \u2013 NYU Local|work=NYU Local}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Child acting===\nWilson became interested in acting after watching her older brother, Danny, appear in television commercials. Initially, Wilson's parents were disinclined but eventually agreed to let her into acting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/04-2013/being-matilda_64967.html |title=Being Matilda |work=Theater Mania |first=Mara |last=Wilson |date=April 22, 2013 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> After appearing in several commercials for business companies, such as [[Lunchables]], [[Bank of America]], [[Texaco]], and [[Marshalls]], Wilson was invited to audition for the 1993 comedy film ''Mrs. Doubtfire.'' Producers were impressed and awarded her the role of Natalie Hillard. The following year, Wilson appeared in the remake of ''Miracle on 34th Street''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-07-27/entertainment/9707250824_1_mara-wilson-starring-role-rock-cafe |title=Mara Wilson's Role Is A Wish Come True |date=July 27, 1997 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |author=Orange County (Calif.) Register |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623061420/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-07-27/entertainment/9707250824_1_mara-wilson-starring-role-rock-cafe |archive-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref> In 1994, she was cast in a recurring role as Nikki Petrova on ''[[Melrose Place]],'' and played Barbara Barton in the television film ''A Time to Heal''.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nWilson sang \"[[Make 'Em Laugh]]\" at the [[67th Academy Awards]] broadcast on March 27, 1995, with [[Tim Curry]] and [[Kathy Najimy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Archerd |first=Army |date=March 14, 1995 |url=https://variety.com/1995/voices/columns/oscars-plan-to-make-em-laugh-1117862661/ |title=Oscars plan to 'Make 'em Laugh' |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]]}}</ref> In 1995, she won the [[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest Award]] for Young Star of the Year. Her film work caught the attention of [[Danny DeVito]], and Wilson was cast as the main protagonist, Matilda Wormwood, in the 1996 film ''Matilda''. Wilson was nominated for three awards for her performance, winning the [[YoungStar Award]] for Best Performance by a Young Actress in a Comedy Film. In 1997, she starred in ''[[A Simple Wish]]'' alongside [[Martin Short]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997/jul/11/entertainment/ca-11517 |title=Short Works Magic in Uneven ''A Simple Wish'' |first=Kenneth |last=Turan |date=July 11, 1997 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |newspaper=[[LA Times]]}}</ref> Although Wilson was nominated for three awards, the film mostly received negative reviews by critics.\n\nIn 1997, Wilson went to a [[Read-through|table reading]] for ''[[What Dreams May Come (film)|What Dreams May Come]]'' starring [[Robin Williams]], but she did not get the part.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/mara-wilson-recalls-robin-williams-grown-ups/story?id=25027733 |title=Mara Wilson Recalls Robin Williams 'Was Different With Grown-Ups' |work=[[ABC News]] |first=Lesley |last=Messer |date=August 18, 2014 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]}}</ref> A year later, Wilson unsuccessfully auditioned for the 1998 remake of Disney's ''[[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|The Parent Trap]];'' the role was given to [[Lindsay Lohan]] after Wilson was deemed too young.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/04/16/matilda-star-mara-wilson-reviews-matilda-the-musical.html |title='Matilda' Star Mara Wilson Reviews 'Matilda the Musical' |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |first=Ramin |last=Setoodeh |date=November 7, 2017 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[The Daily Beast Company LLC.]]}}</ref> In 1999, she portrayed Willow Johnson in the 1999 [[Disney Channel]] television film ''[[Balloon Farm (film)|Balloon Farm]],'' based on a fiction book.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/mar/27/entertainment/ca-21390 |title=Rip Torn, Mara Wilson Help Keep Disney's 'Balloon Farm' Aloft |first=Lynne |last=Heffley |date=March 27, 1999 |newspaper=[[LA Times]] |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2000, Wilson appeared in the fantasy-adventure family film ''[[Thomas and the Magic Railroad]],'' which was her last film as a child actor. Wilson retired from film work shortly afterward.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/marawilson |title=Mara Wilson Interview |magazine=[[contactmusic.com]] |date=January 7, 2009 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> Wilson received a film script for the 2001 film ''[[Donnie Darko]]'', but she declined to audition for the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/mara-wilson-sickness-induced-reason-she-hates-gary-211227 |title=Mara Wilson on the sickness-induced reason she hates Gary Jules' \"Mad World\" |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |first=Marah |last=Eakin |date=April 11, 2014 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Onion, Inc.]]}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u2013present ===\nIn 2012, Wilson appeared briefly in one episode of a [[web series]] called ''Missed Connection'' in the role of Bitty and made special appearances on internet review shows for ''[[Channel Awesome|That Guy with the Glasses]]''\u2014most notably a comedic turn playing an adult Matilda during a review of ''Matilda'' by The Nostalgia Chick, [[Lindsay Ellis (Nostalgia Chick)|Lindsay Ellis]]. That year, Wilson explained why she quit film acting; \"Film acting is not very fun. Doing the same thing over and over again until, in the director's eyes, you 'get it right', does not allow for very much creative freedom. The best times I had on film sets were the times the director let me express myself, but those were rare.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/child-star-mara-wilson-why-i-quit-film-acting-2012174 |title=Child Star Mara Wilson: Why I Quit Film Acting |date=April 17, 2012 |magazine=[[usmagazine.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828171801/https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/child-star-mara-wilson-why-i-quit-film-acting-2012174/ |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |first=Zach |last=Johnson |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[American Media Inc.]]}}</ref> However, Wilson made a return to acting in the 2015 comedy-drama film ''Billie Bob Joe.''\n\nWilson has a recurring role on the podcast ''[[Welcome to Night Vale]]'' as \"The Faceless Old Woman Who Secretly Lives in Your Home\", as well as her own storytelling show called ''What Are You Afraid Of?''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/37/3/24-mara-wilson-storytelling-union-hall-2014-01-17-bk_37_3.html |title=Mara Wilson's 'What are you afraid of?' at Union Hall |newspaper=[[The Brooklyn Paper]] |first=Meredith |last=Deliso |date=January 15, 2014 |access-date=July 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.longreads.com/2014/11/26/interview-former-matilda-star-mara-wilson-on-leaving-hollywood-and-becoming-a-writer/ |title=Interview: Former 'Matilda' Star Mara Wilson on Leaving Hollywood and Becoming a Writer |work=[[Longreads]] Blog |first=Adele |last=Oliveira |date=November 26, 2014 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, Wilson made a brief return to television in a ''Mrs. Doubtfire''-inspired episode of ''[[Broad City]]''; she played a waitress where the comical Heimlich scene from the movie was reenacted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/755164/how-broad-city-convinced-mara-wilson-to-get-back-into-acting-with-a-mrs-doubtfire-twist |title=How Broad City Convinced Mara Wilson to Get Back Into Acting |publisher=[[E! News]] |work=[[E! Online]] |first=Kendall |last=Fisher |date=April 8, 2016 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/article/mara-wilson-mrs-doubtfire-broad-city-cameo |title=Mara Wilson on Her Return to Acting for Broad City's Homage to Mrs. Doubtfire: 'This Movie Did a Lot for Me' |first=Karen |last=Mizoguchi |date=April 8, 2016 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=June 15, 2016 |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref> That same year, she also voiced Jill Pill, a writer/director anthropomorphic spider, in season 3 of ''[[BoJack Horseman]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.avclub.com/tvclub/bojack-horseman-rides-season-three-atop-secretaria-239946 |title=BoJack Horseman rides into season three atop the Secretariat Oscar campaign |date=July 22, 2016 |publisher=[[Onion, Inc.]] |first=Les |last=Chappell |access-date=August 4, 2019 |work=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nIn May 2013, Wilson wrote an article for online magazine [[Cracked.com]], offering her opinion of the delinquency of some former child stars.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mara |last=Wilson |work=[[Cracked.com]] |title=7 Reasons Child Stars Go Crazy (An Insider's Perspective) |url=http://www.cracked.com/blog/7-reasons-child-stars-go-crazy-an-insiders-perspective/ |date=May 28, 2013 |access-date=June 13, 2013}}</ref> As of 2013, she worked for [[Publicolor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehollywoodnews.com/2013/03/09/where-are-they-now-1-mara-wilson/ |title=Where Are They Now? #1: Mara Wilson |work=thehollywoodnews.com |first=Paul |last=Health |date=March 9, 2013 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> Her play ''Sheeple'' was produced in 2013 for the [[New York International Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc-arts.org/events/73208/sheeple |title=Sheeple |work=[[NYC Arts]] |date=August 10, 2013 |access-date=June 13, 2013 |publisher=[[Alliance for the Arts]]}}</ref> In an interview that December, Wilson stated that her film acting days are over,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://parade.com/236764/scottneumyer/mara-wilson-talks-matilda-the-loss-of-her-mother-and-quitting-acting/ |title=Mara Wilson Talks Matilda, the Loss of Her Mother, and Quitting Acting |last=Neumyer |first=Scott |magazine=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |date=December 2, 2013 |access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> and that she is instead focusing on writing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/624729/matilda-reunion-mara-wilson-and-kiami-davael-are-still-friends-and-hanging-out-19-years-later-see-the-photo |title=Matilda Reunion! Mara Wilson and Kiami Davael Are Still Friends and Hanging Out 19 Years Later\u2014See the Photo! |date=February 11, 2015 |work=[[E! News]] |publisher=[[E! Online]] |access-date=August 4, 2019 |first=Natalie |last=Finn}}</ref> Her book ''Where Am I Now?: True Stories of Girlhood and Accidental Fame'' was published on September 13, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://aux.avclub.com/mara-wilson-shines-like-a-beacon-in-the-witty-and-touch-1798188733 |title=Mara Wilson shines like a beacon in the witty and touching Where Am I Now? |last=Chavez |first=Danette |date=December 9, 2016 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=June 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Onion, Inc.]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAt age 12, Wilson was diagnosed with [[obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/mara-wilson-interview/ |title=What is Mara Wilson afraid of? |work=[[The Daily Dot]] |first=Claire |last=Linic |date=November 14, 2014 |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Complex Media, Inc.]]}}</ref> She has also been diagnosed with [[ADHD]].<ref>{{cite interview |last=Wilson |first=Mara |interviewer=Judy Gold |title=Kill Me Now with Judy Gold - Episode 3 |url=https://omny.fm/shows/kill-me-now-with-judy-gold/episode-3-mara-wilson |date=May 19, 2015 |work=Omny Studio |access-date=April 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416200359/https://omny.fm/shows/kill-me-now-with-judy-gold/episode-3-mara-wilson |archive-date=April 16, 2018}}</ref> In 2015, she collaborated with Project UROK, a nonprofit organization whose mission is to aid teens with mental illness.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/mara-wilson-mental-illness_us_56181df6e4b0dbb8000e9ed9 |title=Mara Wilson On Dealing With Mental Illness In The Public Eye |first=Lindsay |last=Holmes |date=October 9, 2015 |publisher=[[Huffington Post Media Group]] |work=[[Huffington Post]] |location=New York City|access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> Wilson appeared in a video in which she talks about the mental illnesses she has experienced, including anxiety, depression, and obsessive-compulsive disorder.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pittman |first=Taylor |date=May 5, 2015 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/05/05/mara-wilson-project-urok_n_7213598.html |title=Mara Wilson's Important Message For Teens Living With Mental Illness |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Verizon Media]]}}</ref> She also discussed her history of mental illness on [[Paul Gilmartin]]'s podcast ''[[The Mental Illness Happy Hour]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mentalpod.com/archives/4171 |title=Mara Wilson |date=September 16, 2016 |work=[[The Mental Illness Happy Hour]] |access-date=February 22, 2018 |first=Paul |last=Gilmartin |author-link=Paul Gilmartin}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2013, Wilson resides in [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/article/mara-wilson-child-star-mrs-doubtfire-matilda-looks-quit-hollywood |title=Mara Wilson: Why Mrs. Doubtfire Star Quit Hollywood over Scrutiny of Her Looks |last=Nelson |first=Jeff |date=August 24, 2016 |magazine=[[People.com]] |access-date=August 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\nWilson is [[bisexual]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Ariel|last=Goldberg|url= https://medium.com/lambdalegal/matildas-bi-and-so-am-i-an-interview-with-mara-wilson-854208a3c0b6|title='Matilda' is Bi and So Am I: an Interview with Mara Wilson|website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|publisher=A Medium Corporation|location=San Francisco, California|date=September 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn an [[NPR]] interview, [[Nancy Cartwright]] stated that a young Mara Wilson was the inspiration for a character's voice on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Bart Sells His Soul]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.feralaudio.com/109-barts-girlfriend-mara-wilson/ |title=Allie Goertz and Julia Prescott interview comics, writers, animators and show creators about their favorite episode of \"The Simpsons.\" |date=August 8, 2017 |first=Julia |last=Prescott |first2=Allie |last2=Goertz |author2-link=Allie Goertz |work=[[Feral Audio]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808195307/http://www.feralaudio.com/109-barts-girlfriend-mara-wilson/ |archive-date=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPolitical commentator, author, and public speaker [[Ben Shapiro]] is her maternal cousin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/benshapiroshow/ep411|title=Ep. 411 - Another Day, Another Mass Shooting (at 44.22 minutes in)|publisher=|accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref> According to Shapiro, Wilson has blocked him on social media platforms,<ref>{{cite tweet |user=benshapiro |last=Shapiro |first=Ben |number=935525346664783873 |date=2017-11-28 |title=I believe she blocked me years ago, before I even knew she was on Twitter.}}</ref> and Wilson has stated that \"growing up is great because you get to choose which relatives you want to spend time with and which ones to cut out of your life without any regret.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MaraWilson |last=Wilson |first=Mara |number=1126244913467641856 |date=2019-05-08 |title=Growing up is great because you get to choose which relatives you want to spend time with and which ones to cut out of your life without any regret}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=wikitable\n|+Mara Wilson film work\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1993 || ''[[Mrs. Doubtfire]]'' || Natalie \"Nattie\" Hillard ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1994 || ''[[Miracle on 34th Street (1994 film)|Miracle on 34th Street]]'' || Susan Walker ||\n|-\n|''[[A Time to Heal (film)|A Time to Heal]]''\n|Barbara Barton\n|Television film\n|-\n| 1996 ||''[[Matilda (1996 film)|Matilda]]''||[[Matilda Wormwood]]||\n|-\n| 1997 ||''[[A Simple Wish]]''|| Anabel Greening ||\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Balloon Farm (film)|Balloon Farm]]''\n|Willow Johnson\n|Television film\n|-\n| 2000 ||''[[Thomas and the Magic Railroad]]''|| Lily Stone ||\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+Mara Wilson television work\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Melrose Place]]''\n| Nicole \"Nikki\" Petrova\n| Recurring role; 5 episodes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Pearl (TV series)|Pearl]]''\n| Samantha Stein\n| Episode: \"The Tutor\"\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Batman Beyond]]''\n| Tamara (voice)\n| Episode: \"Mind Games\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n| ''[[Broad City]]''\n| Waitress\n| Episode: \"Burning Bridges\"\n|-\n| ''[[BoJack Horseman]]''\n| Jill Pill (voice)\n| Recurring role; 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[Big Hero 6: The Series]]''\n| Liv Amara (voice)\n| Recurring role\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Mara Wilson Internet series work\n|-\n! Year\n! Title series\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2012\n| ''[[Nostalgia Critic]]''\n|rowspan=2|Herself\n| Episode: \"A Simple Wish\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thatguywiththeglasses.com/videolinks/thatguywiththeglasses/nostalgia-critic/35109-a-simple-wish |title=A Simple Wish |publisher=Thatguywiththeglasses.com |date=May 1, 2012 |accessdate=August 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724202405/http://thatguywiththeglasses.com/videolinks/thatguywiththeglasses/nostalgia-critic/35109-a-simple-wish |archive-date=July 24, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Nostalgia Chick''\n| Episode: \"Matilda\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thatguywiththeglasses.com/videolinks/team-nchick/nostalgia-chick/36832-matilda |title=Matilda |publisher=Thatguywiththeglasses.com |date=October 11, 2012 |accessdate=August 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816122800/http://thatguywiththeglasses.com/videolinks/team-nchick/nostalgia-chick/36832-matilda |archive-date=August 16, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Demo Reel''\n| Donnie DuPre's wife (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]] (Bromance Version)\"\n|-\n| ''Shut Up and Talk''\n| Herself\n| Episode: \"Guest: Mara Wilson\"\n|-\n|''Missed Connection''\n||Bitty\n| Episode: \"Bad Dates\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comediva.com/missed-connection-bad-dates#synopsis |title=Missed Connection: \"Bad Dates\" |publisher=Comediva |date=January 30, 2012 |accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n||2013\n| ''[[Welcome to Night Vale]]''\n|The Faceless Old Woman\nWho Secretly Lives In Your Home\n| Episodes:\n*\"26 \u2013 Faceless Old Woman\"\n*\"31 \u2013 A Blinking Light up on the Mountain\"\n*\"Condos\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://podbay.fm/show/536258179/e/1379228400?autostart=1 |title=31 \u2013 A Blinking Light up on the Mountain from Welcome to Night Vale on podbay |publisher=Podbay.fm|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n*\"The Debate\"\n*\"49 \u2013 Old Oak Doors\"\n*\"53 \u2013 The September Monologues\"\n*\"The Librarian\"\n*\"65 \u2013 Voicemail\"\n*\"66 \u2013 worms...\"\n*\u201c106 - Filings\u201d\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2014\n| ''[[Keith and The Girl]]''\n| rowspan=\"9\" | Herself\n| Episode: \"2002: Boobs\"<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.keithandthegirl.com/Show-Detail/3324/Boobs.aspx |title=Boobs (Keith and The Girl) \u2013 Comedy Talk Show & Podcast |publisher=Keith and The Girl |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Nostalgia Chick''\n| Episode: \"Nostalgic Foods of Yore\"\n|-\n|''Amy Poehler's Smart Girls''\n|Episode: \"The In Too Steep Tea Party\"\n|-\n|''Maven of the Eventide''\n|Pumpktoberfest Vlogs, Episodes 5 and 12\n|-\n|''I Don't Even Own a Television''\n|Episode: \"016 \u2014 Covert Conception (w/ Mara Wilson)\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idontevenownatelevision.com/2014/08/08/covert-conception-w-mara-wilson/|title=016 -- Covert Conception (w/ Mara Wilson)|date=August 8, 2014