le=American FactFinder }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0623677<ref>{{gnis|623677}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Comstock Park''' is a [[census-designated place]] and [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Alpine Township, Michigan|Alpine Township]] and [[Plainfield Township, Kent County, Michigan|Plainfield Township]], [[Kent County, Michigan|Kent County]], [[Michigan]], in the [[Grand Rapids metropolitan area]], United States.<ref name=ComstockParkCDPMap>\"[http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st26_mi/place/p2617700_comstock_park/DC10BLK_P2617700_001.pdf 2010 CENSUS - CENSUS BLOCK MAP: Comstock Park CDP, MI].\" () [[U.S. Census Bureau]]. Retrieved on December 25, 2012.</ref><ref name=AlpineTwpMap>\"[http://www.alpinetwp.org/docs/2010%20Alpine%20Zoning%20Map231811.pdf 2010 Zoning Map ADOPTED BY THE ALPINE TOWNSHIP BOARD JUNE 18, 1990 AS AMENDED THROUGH ORD. No. 10-01] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806214028/http://www.alpinetwp.org/docs/2010%20Alpine%20Zoning%20Map231811.pdf |date=August 6, 2011 }}.\" () Alpine Township, Michigan. Retrieved on December 27, 2012.</ref><ref name=PlainfieldTwpMap>\"[http://www.plainfieldchartertwp.org/pdf/misc/PCTstreets.pdf Street Map].\" () [[Plainfield Township, Kent County, Michigan]]. Retrieved on December 25, 2012.</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the community had a population of 10,088,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617700| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Comstock Park CDP, Michigan| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=March 19, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213063337/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617700| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> with the majority (9,044) living in Alpine Township.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US260810184017700| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Comstock Park CDP (part), Alpine Township, Kent County, Michigan| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=March 19, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214000935/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US260810184017700| archive-date=February 14, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n \nThe area is known for the flooding it experiences every spring from the [[Grand River (Michigan)|Grand River]], which runs just east of the community.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nComstock Park is the home of the [[West Michigan Whitecaps]], an affiliate of the [[Detroit Tigers]].\n\nComstock Park is known for its golf courses, having two courses and 45 total holes of golf in town. The best-known of these is Scott Lake Golf and Practice Center, the winner of the 2011 Michigan Golf Course Owners Association \"Golf Course of the Year\" and the 2012 National Golf Course Owners Association \"Golf Course of the Year.\n\n==History==\nIn 1838 a settlement known as \"North's Mill\" was established by Daniel North. The name changed to \"Mill Creek\" in 1848. The area became a major transportation hub, serving both the [[Grand Rapids and Indiana Railroad]] and [[Chicago and Western Indiana Railroad]], and set the tone for becoming the northern Grand Rapids-area crossroads it is today. It was renamed \"Comstock Park\" in 1906, after [[Charles C. Comstock]], who represented the district in Congress in 1885 and 1886. Comstock lived on the other side of the Grand River and never in Comstock Park.\n\n==Geography==\nComstock Park is in western Kent County, in the southeast corner of Alpine Township and the southwest corner of Plainfield Charter Township. It is bordered to the south by the city of [[Walker, Michigan|Walker]], to the west by Cordes Avenue and Alpine Avenue, to the north by 6 Mile Road, and to the east by Pine Island Drive, West River Drive, and [[U.S. Route 131]], which leads south {{convert|5|mi|0}} to downtown [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]. The [[Grand River (Michigan)|Grand River]] flows just to the east of the CDP.\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the Comstock Park CDP has a total area of {{convert|10.1|sqkm|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|0.02|sqkm|order=flip|2}}, or 0.23%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Yorkcreek.jpg|thumb|One of Comstock Park's many sprawling apartment complexes]]\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 10,674 people, 4,441 households, and 2,513 families residing in the community.  The [[population density]] was 2,735.0 per square mile (1,056.7/km\u00b2).  There were 4,654 housing units at an average density of 1,192.5 per square mile (460.7/km\u00b2). [[File:Fifth third ballpark.jpg|thumb|left|5/3 Ballpark hosts the West Michigan Whitecaps in addition to seasonal concerts, festivals, and the famous \"Night Lights\" holiday light display.]] The racial makeup of the community was 87.30% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.91% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.77% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.92% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.06% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 3.33% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.73% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 7.22% of the population.\n\nOf the 4,441 households, 29.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 39.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 43.4% were not families. About 27.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 4.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 2.98.\n\nIn the community, the population was distributed as with 23.8% under the age of 18, 20.4% from 18 to 24, 31.8% from 25 to 44, 16.5% from 45 to 64, and 7.6% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 27 years. For every 100 females, there were 101.9 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 99.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the community was $40,202, and for a family was $47,154. Males had a median income of $36,076 versus $26,331 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the community was $19,911.  About 7.9% of families and 9.7% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 12.7% of those under age 18 and 2.2% of those age 65 or over.\n\n{{Coord|43|02|19|N|85|40|12|W|type:city_region:US-MI_source:GNIS|display=title}}\n\n==Transportation==\nComstock Park, since it became a hub for rail transit in the mid 19th century, has evolved into a transportation crossroads in northern suburban Grand Rapids. \"The Park\" is quickly accessible from surrounding suburbs, as well as downtown Grand Rapids.\n\n[[File:White Pine Trail, Michigan.jpg|thumb|right|The White Pine Trail brings bicyclists north to [[Rockford, Michigan|Rockford]], or south to downtown Grand Rapids.]]\n\n[[File:Large the-rapid-file-bus.jpg|thumb|right|The Rapid bus line serves Comstock Park via Alpine Avenue.]]\n\n===Major thoroughfares===\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|131}}\n*{{jct|state=MI|MI|37}} / Alpine Avenue\n*West River Drive\n*4 Mile Road\n\n===Other transit===\n*A bus line serves Comstock Park via Alpine Ave/M37 through the [[Interurban Transit Partnership]], or The Rapid.\n*[[White Pine Trail State Park]] runs through the core of the community, giving residents access to {{convert|92|mi}} of biking/walking trails heading north to [[Cadillac, Michigan|Cadillac]] or south, connecting to [[Kent Trails]], which goes through Grand Rapids, [[Grandville, Michigan|Grandville]], [[Walker, Michigan|Walker]], [[Wyoming, Michigan|Wyoming]], and [[Byron Township, Michigan|Byron Township]].\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary and secondary schools===\n[[Comstock Park Public Schools]] serves the community. The district headquarters are in the Comstock Park CDP and in [[Plainfield Township, Kent County, Michigan|Plainfield Township]].<ref name=ComstockParkCDPMap/><ref name=PlainfieldTwpMap/><ref>\"[http://www.cppschools.com/District/CentralOffice.aspx Comstock Park Central Office] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014233727/http://www.cppschools.com/District/CentralOffice.aspx |date=2012-10-14 }}.\" Comstock Park Public Schools. Retrieved on December 25, 2012. \"101 School Street NE Comstock Park, MI 49321\"</ref>\n\nStoney Creek Elementary School has Preschool, kindergarten, PPI and grades 1 and 2. Pine Island Elementary School serves 3 through 5. Mill Creek Middle School has grades 6 through 8. Comstock Park High School serves grades 9 through 12.<ref name=Aboutour>\"[http://www.cppschools.com/District/AboutOurDistrict.aspx ABOUT OUR DISTRICT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104024741/http://www.cppschools.com/District/AboutOurDistrict.aspx |date=2013-01-04 }}.\" Comstock Park Public Schools. Retrieved on December 25, 2012.</ref> All schools except Pine Island are located in the CDP limits.<ref name=CPPSSchooladdresses>\"[http://www.cppschools.com/Schools.aspx Schools] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224043436/http://www.cppschools.com/Schools.aspx |date=2012-12-24 }}.\" Comstock Park Public Schools. Retrieved on December 27, 2012. \"Greenridge Elementary Pre-School & ECSE 3825 Oakridge, NE Comstock Park, MI 49321\" and \"Stoney Creek Elementary Grades: K, 1, 2 200 Lantern Dr. NW Comstock Park, MI 49321\" and \"Pine Island Elementary Grades 3, 4, & 5 6101 Pine Island Drive Comstock Park, MI 49321\" and \"Comstock Park High School Grades 9-12 150 Six Mile Rd. NE Comstock Park, MI 49321-0900\"</ref>\n\nThe [[Kent District Library]] KDL Service Center is near Comstock Park, in Plainfield Township.<ref name=ComstockParkCDPMap/><ref name=PlainfieldTwpMap/><ref>\"[http://www.kdl.org/about/contact_us Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116111902/http://www.kdl.org/about/contact_us |date=2013-01-16 }}.\" [[Kent District Library]]. Retrieved on December 27, 2012. \"KDL Service Center 814 West River Center Dr. NE Comstock Park, MI</ref> The Alpine Branch Library is near the CDP, in [[Alpine Township, Michigan|Alpine Township]].<ref name=ComstockParkCDPMap/><ref name=AlpineTwpMap/><ref>\"[http://www.alpinetwp.org/department.php?d=12 KDL Branch Library] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117041024/http://www.alpinetwp.org/department.php?d=12 |date=November 17, 2012 }}.\" Alpine Township, Michigan. Retrieved on December 27, 2012. \"KDL Library Branch 5255 Alpine Ave NW Comstock Park, MI 49321\"</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Michigan}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.comstockparkdda.org Comstock Park Downtown Development Authority]\n\n{{Kent County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kent County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Grand Rapids metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1838]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kent County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:1838 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comstock_Park,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Bey Yaar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Bey Yaar\n| image = Bey Yaar poster.jpg\n| caption = Official poster\n| director = [[Abhishek Jain]]\n| producer = Nayan Jain\n| writer =Bhavesh Mandalia<br />Niren Bhatt\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Darshan Jariwala]]\n* [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]\n* Aarti Patel\n* Amit Mistry\n* [[Kavin Dave]]\n* Divyang Thakkar\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]]\n* Samvedna Suwalka\n}}\n| music = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Pushkar Singh\n| editing = Satchit Puranik<br />Nirav Panchal\n| studio = [[CineMan Productions]]\n| distributor = CineMan Productions\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2014|8|29}}\n| runtime = 150 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 150:43--><ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3590482/|title=Bey Yaar (2014) - IMDb|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| country = India\n| language = Gujarati\n| budget = {{INR|link=yes}}2.25 [[crore]]<ref name=\"SadWeekly 2015\">{{cite web |title='\u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0a88\u0ab6' \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 '\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0'\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9c\u0a95 \u0a85\u0aad\u0abf\u0ab7\u0ac7\u0a95 \u0a9c\u0ac8\u0aa8 \u0a95\u0ab9\u0ac7 \u0a9b\u0ac7...\u0a8f \u0a98\u0a9f\u0aa8\u0abe\u0a8f \u0a9c \u0aae\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aab\u0abf\u0ab2\u0acd\u0aae \u0aac\u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0aa7\u0a97\u0ab6\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0ab5\u0aa7\u0ac1 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0a97\u0a9f\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ac0| url=http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 | language=gu | date=2 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093349/http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 |archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross = {{Estimation}}<!--Per WT:ICTF consensus--> {{INR|8.5 crore}}<ref  name=\"Hindu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/wrongside-raju-gujarati-film-industry-still-a-work-in-progress/article9017546.ece|title=Gujarati film industry, still a work in progress|date=August 20, 2016|author=Hari Narayan|work=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Bey Yaar''''' ({{trans|'Oh friend!'\u2014An expression}}) is a 2015 Indian [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]-language [[coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] film directed by [[Abhishek Jain]]. The film is about friendship and two friends. The film stars [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]], [[Darshan Jariwala]], Divyang Thakkar, [[Pratik Gandhi]], Amit Mistry, Samvedna Suwalka. The film was released on 29 August 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2014/08/01/bey-yaars-theatrical-trailer-launched/|title=Bey Yaar\u2019s Theatrical Trailer Launched|date=1 August 2014|publisher=DeshGujarat}}</ref> to positive reviews and became a box-office success. It completed 50 weeks in theatres.<ref name=\"50 weeks\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/gujarati-film-bey-yaar-completes-50-weeks-in-theatres/|title=Gujarati film \u2018Bey Yaar\u2019 completes 50 weeks in theatres|work=IANS|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|date=8 August 2015}}</ref> The film was screened at [[New York Indian Film Festival]], becoming the first ever Gujarati film hosted by the festival.<ref name=\"NIYFF\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/Gujarati-movie-Bey-Yaar-has-been-now-officially-selected-for-New-York-Film-Festival-2015/articleshow/46699766.cms|title=Bey Yaar goes international once again|date=26 March 2015|author=Shreya Iyer}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nChildhood friends Chintan \"Chako\" (Divyang Thakkar) and Tapan \"Tino\" ([[Pratik Gandhi]]) aspire to invest in a real estate project called ''The Other Side'', located near the scenic [[Nal Sarovar Bird Sanctuary|Nal Savorar]] area and their residence of [[Ahmedabad]]. They currently work as [[Pharmaceutical sales representative|MRs]] while hoping to make quick money through a [[Godman (India)|Godman]] who promises to triple their profit. The Godman turns out to be part of a larger con and his scheme is discovered by the police. As a result, Chako and Tino are scammed out of [[\u20b9]]1,80,000 (or 180,000 [[rupee]]s).\n\nChako's father, Jeetu ([[Darshan Jariwala]]), runs a small local tea stall, in which hangs a painting from a prominent artist named M.F. Hassan (based on the late [[M.F. Husain]]). The piece was gifted to Jeetu as a sign of their close friendship, before Hassan's rise to prominence and eventual death. Upon learning that Jeetu's tea stall painting is highly coveted, Tino comes up with another idea to secure an investment with ''The Other Side'': secretly replace the painting with an identical fake one, and then loan the original for cash. Initially hesitant but desperate, Chako assists in the plan along with their friend Uday ([[Kavin Dave]]), an avid painter who begrudgingly agrees to compose an exact copy of the piece himself.\n\nWith the switch successful, Chako and Tino mortgage the original painting to a local art dealer, Y.B. Gandhi ([[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]). Shortly thereafter, however, Gandhi informs Chako that the painting he received is fake and that someone else had tried to sell the same painting to another dealer. Gandhi convinces Chako that either Tino had double-crossed him, or that his father had been lying about the painting's authenticity. Chako returns the money back to Gandhi, and angrily confronts Tino, who indeed went to a separate dealer, but was sent by Uday for an art survey only. Chako then meets his father and accuses him of confabulating a friendship. Angered by the accusations and hurt by Chako's loss of the painting, Jeetu kicks him out of the house.\n\nThe M.F. Hassan painting, however, was an original all along, and Gandhi - whom Hassan hated and never lent his work  to - had cheated Chako and Tino out of the painting. Gandhi then publicly humiliates Jeetu by telling the press he never had a friendship with Hassan, and that the stories of him making his paintings at the tea stall are all false.\n\nHoping to redeem themselves, Chako and Tino devise a plan to take advantage of Gandhi's own greed in order to get the painting back for Jeetu. Helping with the elaborate scheme include Uday and Jigisha (Samvedna Suwalka), Tino's girlfriend. They hire a method actor named Pranav (Amit Mistry) to pose as \"Prabodh Gupta\", a fictitious international artist from [[Bihar]] whose work has yet to be exhibited in [[India]]. The group successfully lures Gandhi into funding a fabricated [[NGO]] and conducting Prabodh's supposed lucrative first exhibition in India, in exchange for the tea stall painting.\n\nPranav and Uday narrowly retrieve the painting on the day of the held exhibition, just as Gandhi realizes that Prabodh is a fraud. He confronts the place of the fake NGO but encounters Chako, Tino, and Jeetu. Chako and Tino demand that he publicly retract his earlier statements about Jeetu, or else be arrested for selling fake paintings and creating the fictitious \"Prabodh Gupta\" himself (since Gandhi was tricked earlier into funding the fake NGO). Realizing his defeat, Gandhi tries to offer money, but Jeetu declines and chastises him for his greed being the reason Hassan never worked with large art curators.\n\nGandhi holds a televised news conference the next morning, apologizing for his previous accusations against Jeetu. Hassan's piece is returned to Jeetu's shop, after he and Chako fully reconcile. Uday, whose own paintings were used as Prabodh's work from earlier, is offered his own local exhibition, attended by much happier Chako and Tino.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Darshan Jariwala]] as Jeetu Bhai\n* [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]] as Y.B. Gandhi\n* Aarti Patel as Chintan's mother\n* Amit Mistry as Pranav a.k.a. Prabodh Gupta\n* [[Kavin Dave]] as Uday\n* [[Divyang Thakkar]] as Chintan aka Chako\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]] as Tapan aka Tino\n* Samvedna Suwalka as Jigisha\n* Subhash Brahmbhatt as Kanakiya\n* [[Abhishek Jain]] as Dev\n* [[Anang Desai]] as Guest Appearance in News Channel Show\n* [[Smit Pandya]] as Beggar\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Darshan Jariwala 001.JPG|thumb|left|250px|[[Darshan Jariwala]], who played a similar role as a father figure in ''[[Ajab Prem Ki Ghazab Kahani]]'', elaborated that each \"character was built differently and that is the beautiful thing about acting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Darshan-Jariwala-My-personal-struggles-have-helped-my-professional-growth/articleshow/46897124.cms|title=Darshan Jariwala: My personal struggles have helped my professional growth|author=Patel, Kalgi|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref>]]\n\n===Development===\nAfter the success of his debut film, ''[[Kevi Rite Jaish]]'', director [[Abhishek Jain]] announced that his second film will be titled ''Bey Yaar'', under his own banner [[CineMan Productions]], and it will be about the \"strength of friendship\". Jain also took inspiration from K.H. Mohammad, who was the owner of a real life [[Ahmedabad]] tea stall, then-named ''Lucky Tea Stall'', and had a painting gifted to him by the late Indian artist [[M.F. Husain]], a close friend and regular customer of the stall. According to the restaurant's current manager, Siddiqui Ansari, Husain had personally presented the painting in 2004 to Mohammad, now deceased. Similar to the film's character Jeetu, as a promise to both Mohammad and Husain, Ansari and original co-partner Kutti Nayar have refused to sell the painting that still hangs in what is now called ''Lucky Restaurant''.<ref name=\"jamuura2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamuura.com/blog/exclusive-abhishek-jain-on-rebooting-gujarati-cinema-part-2/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Abhishek Jain On Rebooting Gujarati Cinema (Part 2)|author=Yash Thakur|publisher=Jamuura|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dna2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lucky-tea-stall-owner-won-t-sell-his-husain-1037539|title=Lucky tea stall owner won\u2019t sell his Husain|author=Soumitra Trivedi|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=June 24, 2006|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dna2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-he-went-fida-over-tea-the-tea-stall-got-lucky-1553242|title=He went 'Fida' over tea, the tea-stall got lucky|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=June 10, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"toi\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Lucky-sends-tea-for-MF-to-Dubai/articleshow/5364126.cms|title=Lucky sends tea for MF to Dubai!|author=Saeed Khan|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=December 22, 2009|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAnnouncing the cast, Abhishek Jain mentioned that the writer of [[OMG \u2013 Oh My God!]] and [[National Film Awards|national award winner]], Bhavesh Mandalia will be co-writing the film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/I-have-enjoyed-co-writing-a-Gujarati-film-Bhavesh-Mandalia/articleshow/38423591.cms|title=I have enjoyed co-writing a Gujarati film: Bhavesh Mandalia|date=15 July 2014|author=Soumitra Das|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref> and composer duo [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] will compose the music for the film. The cast included veteran Gujarati theatre and [[Hindi cinema]] actors like [[Darshan Jariwala]], Amit Mistry among others.<ref name=dg>{{cite web|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2013/11/29/kevi-rite-jaish-team-announces-next-gujarati-film-bey-yaar/|title=Kevi Rite Jaish team announces next Gujarati film \u2013 Bey Yaar|date=29 November 2013|publisher=DeshGujarat}}</ref> [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]] and [[Kavin Dave]] will be making their debuts in Gujarati movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Kavin-Dave-makes-his-Gujarati-debut-in-Bey-Yaar/articleshow/39611330.cms|title=Kavin Dave makes his Gujarati debut in Bey Yaar|author=Navya Malini|date=4 August 2014}}</ref> Several notable Gujaratis appeared as [[cameo appearance|cameos]] in the film, including columnist [[Jay Vasavada]], author Tushar Shukla, actor Archan Trivedi, art promoter [[Sonal Ambani]] and critic S.D. Desai.<ref name=am>{{cite news|url=http://www.ahmedabadmirror.com/entertainment/hip-happening/Bey-Yaar-How-Gujarati-are-You/articleshow/42741924.cms|title =Bey yaar, how Gujarati are you?|author=Priya Adhyaru Majithia|publisher=[[Ahmedabad Mirror]] |date =18 September 2014|accessdate =20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe film was shot in [[Ahmedabad]], specifically at 50 different locations in 35 days.<ref name=am/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=44594&boxid=36204&ed_date=2014-02-12&ed_code=1310009&ed_page=1|title='Bey yaar...film toh ready chhe, bakaa!\u2019|author=Kinjal Shah-Desai|date=12 February 2014|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Talking about filming locations, Abhishek Jain said, \"We have shot in the most rustic locales of Ahmedabad to bring out the real essence of the city in every scene.\"<ref name=\"FilmReady\"/> In March 2014, it was announced that the film is almost ready.<ref name=\"FilmReady\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-its-almost-ready/articleshow/32953767.cms|title=\u2018Bey Yaar\u2019 it\u2019s almost ready|date=30 March 2014|author=Shreya Iyer|publisher=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref>\n\nTo help with keeping the film's principal photography organized, Jain revealed in an interview that he had 10 assistants for ''Bey Yaar''. He wanted to narrow his responsibilities towards directing, a desire which inspired him to also hire fellow [[Whistling Woods International Institute|Whistling Woods International]] film school alum Amit Desai, who serves as the movie's [[Executive producer|Creative/Executive Producer]]. In an interview with his Alma mater, Desai said that all business-related and marketing choices for ''Bey Yaar'' were ultimately decided by him.<ref name=\"jamuura1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamuura.com/blog/exclusive-abhishek-jain-on-rebooting-gujarati-cinema-part-1/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Abhishek Jain On Rebooting Gujarati Cinema (Part 1)|author=Yash Thakur|publisher=Jamuura|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"amitdesaiimdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3213519/|title=Amit Desai - IMDb|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"wwiyoutube\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X6DsUfY1DgE|title=In Conversation with Creative Producer of Bey Yaar, Amit Desai, a WWI Alumnus|publisher=[[Whistling Woods International Institute|Whistling Woods International]]|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Bey Yaar\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2014|8|10}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 16:45\n| label      = Cineman Productions Limited\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Entertainment (2014 film)|Entertainment]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Finding Fanny]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\nMusic for the film is composed by [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hungama.com/#/music/album-bey-yaar-songs/2602359|title=Bey yaar Songs|accessdate=22 August 2014|publisher=Hungama}}</ref> The director Abhishek Jain said, about the music of the film, \"With Bey Yaar's music we are trying to create a friendship anthem\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/music/Abhishek-Jains-Bey-Yaar-has-the-kind-of-music-which-will-instantly-connect-with-the-youth/articleshow/37122846.cms|title=With Bey Yaar\u2019s music we are trying to create a friendship anthem: Abhishek Jain|date=24 June 2014|author=Shreya Iyer}}</ref> Music review site ''Milliblog'' reviewed the soundtrack as \"short but competent affair\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2014/08/21/bey-yaar-music-review-gujarati-sachin-jigar/|title=Bey Yaar (Music review), Gujarati \u2013 Sachin-Jigar|author=Karthik|date=21 August 2014|publisher=Milliblog}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 16:45\n| headline = Track list\n| all_music = \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = Bey Yaar Sapna Nava\n| lyrics1 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra1 = {{nowrap|Madhav Krishna, Darshan Raval}}\n| length1 = 3:53\n| title2 = Bey Yaar Tara Vina\n| lyrics2 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra2 = [[Sachin Sanghvi]]\n| length2 = 4:55\n| title3 = Rakhad Rakhad\n| lyrics3 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra3 = [[Keerthi Sagathia]]\n| length3 = 4:03\n| title4 = Peechha Raja\n| lyrics4 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra4 = [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]]\n| length4 = 3:54\n}}\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2014, the producers released the teaser<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaars-first-teaser-creates-a-buzz/articleshow/39100873.cms|title=Bey Yaar's first teaser creates a buzz|date=27 July 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> and poster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-teaser-and-first-look-is-out/articleshow/39273842.cms|title=First look of Bey Yaar is out|date=27 July 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]|author=Navya Malini}}</ref> The trailer was released online on 1 August 2014. The theatrical trailer was launched on 4 August 2014 at Alpha One Mall in Ahmedabad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bey Yaar theatrical trailer launched at Cinepolis Ahmedabad|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Bey-Yaar-theatrical-trailer-launched-at-Cinepolis-Ahmedabad/articleshow/39605713.cms|work=The Times of India|date=4 August 2014|accessdate =18 August 2014}}</ref> The film was released on 29 August 2014.\n\nThe movie was initially released at [[Ahmedabad]], [[Surat]], and [[Vadodara]]. After the great response in the first week,<ref name=\"BOSuccess\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Gujarati/Movies/Bey-Yaar-goes-housefull-on-weekend-in-Ahmedabad-multiplexes/articleshow/41501556.cms|title=Bey Yaar goes housefull on weekend in Ahmedabad multiplexes|author=Shruti Jambhekar|date=2 Sep 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref> the movie was released in [[Rajkot]], [[Jamnagar]], and [[Bhavnagar]] in the second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Beyyaarthefilm/photos/a.662555447154595.1073741835.555091901234284/685075831569223/?type=1|title=Bey Yaar will very soon release in Rajkot, Jamnagar and Bhavnagar!|date=3 Sep 2014}}</ref> It expanded its presence across the multiplexes in Gujarat with 127 shows daily in the fourth week.<ref name=\"am\" /> After the success, it was released in [[Mumbai]] and [[Delhi]] as well.<ref name=\"success\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-completes-a-month-in-theatres/articleshow/43883149.cms|title=Bey Yaar completes a month in theatres|date=30 September 2014|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> Subsequently, It was released in [[Melbourne]], [[Sydney]], and [[Brisbane]] in Australia on 9 October 2014. It was released in the US the next month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-to-be-screened-in-Australia/articleshow/44425452.cms|title=Bey Yaar to be screened in Australia|first=Shreya|last=Iyer|date= 3 October 2014|accessdate =9 October 2014}}</ref> Eventually, the film was released across six continents, the first [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] film to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/index.php/articles/display_article/dhoom-on-foreign-soil-macavati-bey-yar|title=Dhoom on foreign soil|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-is-released-worlwide-including-USA-New-Zealand-Australia-Dubai-and-Oman/articleshow/45241152.cms|title=Gujarati movie Bey Yaar goes global|date=23 November 2014|author=Navya Malini}}</ref> The DVD Home media was released in June 2015.<ref name=\"Patel 2015\">{{cite web | last=Patel | first=Ano | title=Abhishek Jain's launches his book | website=The Times of India | date=2015-06-01  | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Abhishek-Jain-Book-and-DVD-launch-for-Abhishek-Jain/articleshow/47512357.cms | accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nCritical reception to the film has been mostly positive. ''[[Divya Bhaskar]]'' praised the film and rated it 3 out of 5 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollywood.divyabhaskar.co.in/article-hf/ENT-BOL-movie-review-bey-yaar-4727933-NOR.html|title=Movie review: Bey Yaar|date=29 August 2014|publisher=[[Divya Bhaskar]]|author=Rajesh Vora}} {{rating|3|5}}</ref> BuddyBits.com rated it 4.5 out of 5 stars praising it to be one of the best films coming out from Gujarati cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buddybits.com/movie-review-bey-yaar/|title=Movie Review: Bey Yaar|date=29 August 2014|publisher=BuddyBits.com|author=Nishit Jariwala}} {{rating|4.5|5}}</ref> ''[[Sandesh (Indian newspaper)|Sandesh]]'' praised it and called it a mature movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandesh.com/article.aspx?newsid=2980475|title=\u2018\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0\u2019:\u0a86 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aab\u0abf\u0ab2\u0acd\u0aae \u0a9c\u0acb\u0a88\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0aa1\u0ac0 \u0a9c\u0ab6\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0ab2\u0ab8\u0acb|date=29 August 2014|publisher=[[Sandesh (Indian newspaper)|Sandesh]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903071820/http://www.sandesh.com/article.aspx?newsid=2980475|archivedate=3 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Times of India]]'' reviewed it positively saying, \"Wonderfully executed, beautifully crafted and crisply edited, the movie makes the popcorn and the hot cuppa more enjoyable.\" and rated it 4 stars out of 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movie-review/Bey-Yaar/articleshow/41451975.cms|title=Bey Yaar|date=1 Sep 2014|author=Navya Malini|publisher=[[Times of India]]}} {{rating|4|5}}</ref> [[Jay Vasavada]] called it, \"Brilliant, Brave, Bright\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/index.php/articles/display_article/anavrut7231|title=Anavrut \u2013 Jay Vasavada|date=3 Sep 2014|publisher=[[Gujarat Samachar]]|author=Jay Vasavada}}</ref> The film was screened at [[New York Indian Film Festival]] on 5 May 2015 and became the first ever Gujarati film to do so.<ref name=\"NIYFF\"/>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film had a limited release across cinemas in [[Gujarat]] and [[Maharashtra]], but was running with packed houses on the day of the release<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=53640&boxid=39410&ed_date=2014-08-30&ed_code=1310009&ed_page=1|title=A full house on Day 1!|date=30 Aug 2014|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]]}}</ref> and continued the success in the first weekend.<ref name=\"BOSuccess\"/> The film completed 100 days in many cities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Bey-Yaar-Gujarati-film-Bey-Yaar-celebrates-100-days-in-the-theatre/articleshow/45519929.cms|title=Cast and crew of Bey Yaar celebrate the perfect century|date=15 December 2014|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> and eventually completed 50 weeks.<ref name=\"50 weeks\"/> The film collected {{INRConvert|8.5|c}} on the box office.<ref  name=\"Hindu\"/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n===14th Annual Transmedia Gujarati Screen & Stage Awards===\nThe film was nominated for 14 out of 16 categories and won total 9 awards, including the best film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-gets-nominated-for-14-categories/articleshow/46389430.cms|title=Bey Yaar gets nominated for 14 categories|date=27 February 2015|author=Shruti Jambekar|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/Bey-Yaar-bags-nine-awards/articleshow/46419657.cms|title=Bey Yaar bags nine awards|author=Shruti Jambekar|date=1 March 2015|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref>\n* '''Best film \u2013 Bey Yaar'''\n* '''Best director \u2013 Abhishek Jain'''\n* '''Best scriptwriter (Story, Screenplay & Dialogue) \u2013 Bhavesh Mandalia, Niren H Bhatt'''\n* Best actor (male) \u2013 Divyang Thakkar\n* Best actor (female) \u2013 Samwedna Suwalka\n* '''Best supporting actor (male) \u2013 [[Darshan Jariwala]]'''\n* Best supporting actor (male) \u2013 Kavin Dave\n* '''Best supporting actor (female) \u2013 Arati Patel'''\n* '''Best actor in a negative role \u2013 [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]'''\n* Best cinematographer \u2013 Pushkar Singh\n* '''Best Editor \u2013 Satchit Puranik,''' '''Nirav Panchal'''\n* '''Best music \u2013 [[Sachin-Jigar]]'''\n* '''Best singer (male) \u2013 Darshan Raval'''\n* '''Best lyrics \u2013 Niren H Bhatt'''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3590482|Bey Yaar}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes | Bey_Yaar | Bey Yaar }}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Beyyaarthefilm Bey Yaar] on [[Facebook]]\n\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Bey Yaar\n| image = Bey Yaar poster.jpg\n| caption = Official poster\n| director = [[Abhishek Jain]]\n| producer = Nayan Jain\n| writer =Bhavesh Mandalia<br />Niren Bhatt\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Darshan Jariwala]]\n* [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]\n* Aarti Patel\n* Amit Mistry\n* [[Kavin Dave]]\n* Divyang Thakkar\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]]\n* Samvedna Suwalka\n}}\n| music = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Pushkar Singh\n| editing = Satchit Puranik<br />Nirav Panchal\n| studio = [[CineMan Productions]]\n| distributor = CineMan Productions\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2014|8|29}}\n| runtime = 150 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 150:43--><ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3590482/|title=Bey Yaar (2014) - IMDb|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| country = India\n| language = Gujarati\n| budget = {{INR|link=yes}}2.25 [[crore]]<ref name=\"SadWeekly 2015\">{{cite web |title='\u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0a88\u0ab6' \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 '\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0'\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9c\u0a95 \u0a85\u0aad\u0abf\u0ab7\u0ac7\u0a95 \u0a9c\u0ac8\u0aa8 \u0a95\u0ab9\u0ac7 \u0a9b\u0ac7...\u0a8f \u0a98\u0a9f\u0aa8\u0abe\u0a8f \u0a9c \u0aae\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aab\u0abf\u0ab2\u0acd\u0aae \u0aac\u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0aa7\u0a97\u0ab6\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0ab5\u0aa7\u0ac1 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0a97\u0a9f\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ac0| url=http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 | language=gu | date=2 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093349/http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 |archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross = {{Estimation}}<!--Per WT:ICTF consensus--> {{INR|8.5 crore}}<ref  name=\"Hindu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/wrongside-raju-gujarati-film-industry-still-a-work-in-progress/article9017546.ece|title=Gujarati film industry, still a work in progress|date=August 20, 2016|author=Hari Narayan|work=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Bey Yaar''''' ({{trans|'Oh friend!'\u2014An expression}}) is a 2015 Indian [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]-language [[coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] film directed by [[Abhishek Jain]]. The film is about friendship and two friends. The film stars [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]], [[Darshan Jariwala]], Divyang Thakkar, [[Pratik Gandhi]], Amit Mistry, Samvedna Suwalka. The film was released on 29 August 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2014/08/01/bey-yaars-theatrical-trailer-launched/|title=Bey Yaar\u2019s Theatrical Trailer Launched|date=1 August 2014|publisher=DeshGujarat}}</ref> to positive reviews and became a box-office success. It completed 50 weeks in theatres.<ref name=\"50 weeks\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/gujarati-film-bey-yaar-completes-50-weeks-in-theatres/|title=Gujarati film \u2018Bey Yaar\u2019 completes 50 weeks in theatres|work=IANS|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|date=8 August 2015}}</ref> The film was screened at [[New York Indian Film Festival]], becoming the first ever Gujarati film hosted by the festival.<ref name=\"NIYFF\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/Gujarati-movie-Bey-Yaar-has-been-now-officially-selected-for-New-York-Film-Festival-2015/articleshow/46699766.cms|title=Bey Yaar goes international once again|date=26 March 2015|author=Shreya Iyer}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nChildhood friends Chintan \"Chako\" (Divyang Thakkar) and Tapan \"Tino\" ([[Pratik Gandhi]]) aspire to invest in a real estate project called ''The Other Side'', located near the scenic [[Nal Sarovar Bird Sanctuary|Nal Savorar]] area and their residence of [[Ahmedabad]]. They currently work as [[Pharmaceutical sales representative|MRs]] while hoping to make quick money through a [[Godman (India)|Godman]] who promises to triple their profit. The Godman turns out to be part of a larger con and his scheme is discovered by the police. As a result, Chako and Tino are scammed out of [[\u20b9]]1,80,000 (or 180,000 [[rupee]]s).\n\nChako's father, Jeetu ([[Darshan Jariwala]]), runs a small local tea stall, in which hangs a painting from a prominent artist named M.F. Hassan (based on the late [[M.F. Husain]]). The piece was gifted to Jeetu as a sign of their close friendship, before Hassan's rise to prominence and eventual death. Upon learning that Jeetu's tea stall painting is highly coveted, Tino comes up with another idea to secure an investment with ''The Other Side'': secretly replace the painting with an identical fake one, and then loan the original for cash. Initially hesitant but desperate, Chako assists in the plan along with their friend Uday ([[Kavin Dave]]), an avid painter who begrudgingly agrees to compose an exact copy of the piece himself.\n\nWith the switch successful, Chako and Tino mortgage the original painting to a local art dealer, Y.B. Gandhi ([[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]). Shortly thereafter, however, Gandhi informs Chako that the painting he received is fake and that someone else had tried to sell the same painting to another dealer. Gandhi convinces Chako that either Tino had double-crossed him, or that his father had been lying about the painting's authenticity. Chako returns the money back to Gandhi, and angrily confronts Tino, who indeed went to a separate dealer, but was sent by Uday for an art survey only. Chako then meets his father and accuses him of confabulating a friendship. Angered by the accusations and hurt by Chako's loss of the painting, Jeetu kicks him out of the house.\n\nThe M.F. Hassan painting, however, was an original all along, and Gandhi - whom Hassan hated and never lent his work  to - had cheated Chako and Tino out of the painting. Gandhi then publicly humiliates Jeetu by telling the press he never had a friendship with Hassan, and that the stories of him making his paintings at the tea stall are all false.\n\nHoping to redeem themselves, Chako and Tino devise a plan to take advantage of Gandhi's own greed in order to get the painting back for Jeetu. Helping with the elaborate scheme include Uday and Jigisha (Samvedna Suwalka), Tino's girlfriend. They hire a method actor named Pranav (Amit Mistry) to pose as \"Prabodh Gupta\", a fictitious international artist from [[Bihar]] whose work has yet to be exhibited in [[India]]. The group successfully lures Gandhi into funding a fabricated [[NGO]] and conducting Prabodh's supposed lucrative first exhibition in India, in exchange for the tea stall painting.\n\nPranav and Uday narrowly retrieve the painting on the day of the held exhibition, just as Gandhi realizes that Prabodh is a fraud. He confronts the place of the fake NGO but encounters Chako, Tino, and Jeetu. Chako and Tino demand that he publicly retract his earlier statements about Jeetu, or else be arrested for selling fake paintings and creating the fictitious \"Prabodh Gupta\" himself (since Gandhi was tricked earlier into funding the fake NGO). Realizing his defeat, Gandhi tries to offer money, but Jeetu declines and chastises him for his greed being the reason Hassan never worked with large art curators.\n\nGandhi holds a televised news conference the next morning, apologizing for his previous accusations against Jeetu. Hassan's piece is returned to Jeetu's shop, after he and Chako fully reconcile. Uday, whose own paintings were used as Prabodh's work from earlier, is offered his own local exhibition, attended by much happier Chako and Tino.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Darshan Jariwala]] as Jeetu Bhai\n* [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]] as Y.B. Gandhi\n* Aarti Patel as Chintan's mother\n* Amit Mistry as Pranav a.k.a. Prabodh Gupta\n* [[Kavin Dave]] as Uday\n* [[Divyang Thakkar]] as Chintan aka Chako\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]] as Tapan aka Tino\n* Samvedna Suwalka as Jigisha\n* Subhash Brahmbhatt as Kanakiya\n* [[Abhishek Jain]] as Dev\n* [[Anang Desai]] as Guest Appearance in News Channel Show\n* [[Smit Pandya]] as Beggar\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Darshan Jariwala 001.JPG|thumb|left|250px|[[Darshan Jariwala]], who played a similar role as a father figure in ''[[Ajab Prem Ki Ghazab Kahani]]'', elaborated that each \"character was built differently and that is the beautiful thing about acting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Darshan-Jariwala-My-personal-struggles-have-helped-my-professional-growth/articleshow/46897124.cms|title=Darshan Jariwala: My personal struggles have helped my professional growth|author=Patel, Kalgi|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref>]]\n\n===Development===\nAfter the success of his debut film, ''[[Kevi Rite Jaish]]'', director [[Abhishek Jain]] announced that his second film will be titled ''Bey Yaar'', under his own banner [[CineMan Productions]], and it will be about the \"strength of friendship\". Jain also took inspiration from K.H. Mohammad, who was the owner of a real life [[Ahmedabad]] tea stall, then-named ''Lucky Tea Stall'', and had a painting gifted to him by the late Indian artist [[M.F. Husain]], a close friend and regular customer of the stall. According to the restaurant's current manager, Siddiqui Ansari, Husain had personally presented the painting in 2004 to Mohammad, now deceased. Similar to the film's character Jeetu, as a promise to both Mohammad and Husain, Ansari and original co-partner Kutti Nayar have refused to sell the painting that still hangs in what is now called ''Lucky Restaurant''.<ref name=\"jamuura2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamuura.com/blog/exclusive-abhishek-jain-on-rebooting-gujarati-cinema-part-2/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Abhishek Jain On Rebooting Gujarati Cinema (Part 2)|author=Yash Thakur|publisher=Jamuura|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dna2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lucky-tea-stall-owner-won-t-sell-his-husain-1037539|title=Lucky tea stall owner won\u2019t sell his Husain|author=Soumitra Trivedi|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=June 24, 2006|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dna2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-he-went-fida-over-tea-the-tea-stall-got-lucky-1553242|title=He went 'Fida' over tea, the tea-stall got lucky|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=June 10, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"toi\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Lucky-sends-tea-for-MF-to-Dubai/articleshow/5364126.cms|title=Lucky sends tea for MF to Dubai!|author=Saeed Khan|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=December 22, 2009|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAnnouncing the cast, Abhishek Jain mentioned that the writer of [[OMG \u2013 Oh My God!]] and [[National Film Awards|national award winner]], Bhavesh Mandalia will be co-writing the film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/I-have-enjoyed-co-writing-a-Gujarati-film-Bhavesh-Mandalia/articleshow/38423591.cms|title=I have enjoyed co-writing a Gujarati film: Bhavesh Mandalia|date=15 July 2014|author=Soumitra Das|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref> and composer duo [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] will compose the music for the film. The cast included veteran Gujarati theatre and [[Hindi cinema]] actors like [[Darshan Jariwala]], Amit Mistry among others.<ref name=dg>{{cite web|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2013/11/29/kevi-rite-jaish-team-announces-next-gujarati-film-bey-yaar/|title=Kevi Rite Jaish team announces next Gujarati film \u2013 Bey Yaar|date=29 November 2013|publisher=DeshGujarat}}</ref> [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]] and [[Kavin Dave]] will be making their debuts in Gujarati movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Kavin-Dave-makes-his-Gujarati-debut-in-Bey-Yaar/articleshow/39611330.cms|title=Kavin Dave makes his Gujarati debut in Bey Yaar|author=Navya Malini|date=4 August 2014}}</ref> Several notable Gujaratis appeared as [[cameo appearance|cameos]] in the film, including columnist [[Jay Vasavada]], author Tushar Shukla, actor Archan Trivedi, art promoter [[Sonal Ambani]] and critic S.D. Desai.<ref name=am>{{cite news|url=http://www.ahmedabadmirror.com/entertainment/hip-happening/Bey-Yaar-How-Gujarati-are-You/articleshow/42741924.cms|title =Bey yaar, how Gujarati are you?|author=Priya Adhyaru Majithia|publisher=[[Ahmedabad Mirror]] |date =18 September 2014|accessdate =20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe film was shot in [[Ahmedabad]], specifically at 50 different locations in 35 days.<ref name=am/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=44594&boxid=36204&ed_date=2014-02-12&ed_code=1310009&ed_page=1|title='Bey yaar...film toh ready chhe, bakaa!\u2019|author=Kinjal Shah-Desai|date=12 February 2014|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Talking about filming locations, Abhishek Jain said, \"We have shot in the most rustic locales of Ahmedabad to bring out the real essence of the city in every scene.\"<ref name=\"FilmReady\"/> In March 2014, it was announced that the film is almost ready.<ref name=\"FilmReady\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-its-almost-ready/articleshow/32953767.cms|title=\u2018Bey Yaar\u2019 it\u2019s almost ready|date=30 March 2014|author=Shreya Iyer|publisher=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref>\n\nTo help with keeping the film's principal photography organized, Jain revealed in an interview that he had 10 assistants for ''Bey Yaar''. He wanted to narrow his responsibilities towards directing, a desire which inspired him to also hire fellow [[Whistling Woods International Institute|Whistling Woods International]] film school alum Amit Desai, who serves as the movie's [[Executive producer|Creative/Executive Producer]]. In an interview with his Alma mater, Desai said that all business-related and marketing choices for ''Bey Yaar'' were ultimately decided by him.<ref name=\"jamuura1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamuura.com/blog/exclusive-abhishek-jain-on-rebooting-gujarati-cinema-part-1/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Abhishek Jain On Rebooting Gujarati Cinema (Part 1)|author=Yash Thakur|publisher=Jamuura|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"amitdesaiimdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3213519/|title=Amit Desai - IMDb|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"wwiyoutube\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X6DsUfY1DgE|title=In Conversation with Creative Producer of Bey Yaar, Amit Desai, a WWI Alumnus|publisher=[[Whistling Woods International Institute|Whistling Woods International]]|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Bey Yaar\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2014|8|10}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 16:45\n| label      = Cineman Productions Limited\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Entertainment (2014 film)|Entertainment]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Finding Fanny]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\nMusic for the film is composed by [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hungama.com/#/music/album-bey-yaar-songs/2602359|title=Bey yaar Songs|accessdate=22 August 2014|publisher=Hungama}}</ref> The director Abhishek Jain said, about the music of the film, \"With Bey Yaar's music we are trying to create a friendship anthem\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/music/Abhishek-Jains-Bey-Yaar-has-the-kind-of-music-which-will-instantly-connect-with-the-youth/articleshow/37122846.cms|title=With Bey Yaar\u2019s music we are trying to create a friendship anthem: Abhishek Jain|date=24 June 2014|author=Shreya Iyer}}</ref> Music review site ''Milliblog'' reviewed the soundtrack as \"short but competent affair\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2014/08/21/bey-yaar-music-review-gujarati-sachin-jigar/|title=Bey Yaar (Music review), Gujarati \u2013 Sachin-Jigar|author=Karthik|date=21 August 2014|publisher=Milliblog}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 16:45\n| headline = Track list\n| all_music = \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = Bey Yaar Sapna Nava\n| lyrics1 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra1 = {{nowrap|Madhav Krishna, Darshan Raval}}\n| length1 = 3:53\n| title2 = Bey Yaar Tara Vina\n| lyrics2 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra2 = [[Sachin Sanghvi]]\n| length2 = 4:55\n| title3 = Rakhad Rakhad\n| lyrics3 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra3 = [[Keerthi Sagathia]]\n| length3 = 4:03\n| title4 = Peechha Raja\n| lyrics4 = Niren Bhatt\n| extra4 = [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]]\n| length4 = 3:54\n}}\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2014, the producers released the teaser<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaars-first-teaser-creates-a-buzz/articleshow/39100873.cms|title=Bey Yaar's first teaser creates a buzz|date=27 July 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> and poster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-teaser-and-first-look-is-out/articleshow/39273842.cms|title=First look of Bey Yaar is out|date=27 July 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]|author=Navya Malini}}</ref> The trailer was released online on 1 August 2014. The theatrical trailer was launched on 4 August 2014 at Alpha One Mall in Ahmedabad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bey Yaar theatrical trailer launched at Cinepolis Ahmedabad|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Bey-Yaar-theatrical-trailer-launched-at-Cinepolis-Ahmedabad/articleshow/39605713.cms|work=The Times of India|date=4 August 2014|accessdate =18 August 2014}}</ref> The film was released on 29 August 2014.\n\nThe movie was initially released at [[Ahmedabad]], [[Surat]], and [[Vadodara]]. After the great response in the first week,<ref name=\"BOSuccess\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Gujarati/Movies/Bey-Yaar-goes-housefull-on-weekend-in-Ahmedabad-multiplexes/articleshow/41501556.cms|title=Bey Yaar goes housefull on weekend in Ahmedabad multiplexes|author=Shruti Jambhekar|date=2 Sep 2014|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref> the movie was released in [[Rajkot]], [[Jamnagar]], and [[Bhavnagar]] in the second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Beyyaarthefilm/photos/a.662555447154595.1073741835.555091901234284/685075831569223/?type=1|title=Bey Yaar will very soon release in Rajkot, Jamnagar and Bhavnagar!|date=3 Sep 2014}}</ref> It expanded its presence across the multiplexes in Gujarat with 127 shows daily in the fourth week.<ref name=\"am\" /> After the success, it was released in [[Mumbai]] and [[Delhi]] as well.<ref name=\"success\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-completes-a-month-in-theatres/articleshow/43883149.cms|title=Bey Yaar completes a month in theatres|date=30 September 2014|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> Subsequently, It was released in [[Melbourne]], [[Sydney]], and [[Brisbane]] in Australia on 9 October 2014. It was released in the US the next month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-to-be-screened-in-Australia/articleshow/44425452.cms|title=Bey Yaar to be screened in Australia|first=Shreya|last=Iyer|date= 3 October 2014|accessdate =9 October 2014}}</ref> Eventually, the film was released across six continents, the first [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] film to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/index.php/articles/display_article/dhoom-on-foreign-soil-macavati-bey-yar|title=Dhoom on foreign soil|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-is-released-worlwide-including-USA-New-Zealand-Australia-Dubai-and-Oman/articleshow/45241152.cms|title=Gujarati movie Bey Yaar goes global|date=23 November 2014|author=Navya Malini}}</ref> The DVD Home media was released in June 2015.<ref name=\"Patel 2015\">{{cite web | last=Patel | first=Ano | title=Abhishek Jain's launches his book | website=The Times of India | date=2015-06-01  | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Abhishek-Jain-Book-and-DVD-launch-for-Abhishek-Jain/articleshow/47512357.cms | accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nCritical reception to the film has been mostly positive. ''[[Divya Bhaskar]]'' praised the film and rated it 3 out of 5 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollywood.divyabhaskar.co.in/article-hf/ENT-BOL-movie-review-bey-yaar-4727933-NOR.html|title=Movie review: Bey Yaar|date=29 August 2014|publisher=[[Divya Bhaskar]]|author=Rajesh Vora}} {{rating|3|5}}</ref> BuddyBits.com rated it 4.5 out of 5 stars praising it to be one of the best films coming out from Gujarati cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buddybits.com/movie-review-bey-yaar/|title=Movie Review: Bey Yaar|date=29 August 2014|publisher=BuddyBits.com|author=Nishit Jariwala}} {{rating|4.5|5}}</ref> ''[[Sandesh (Indian newspaper)|Sandesh]]'' praised it and called it a mature movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandesh.com/article.aspx?newsid=2980475|title=\u2018\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0\u2019:\u0a86 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aab\u0abf\u0ab2\u0acd\u0aae \u0a9c\u0acb\u0a88\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0aa1\u0ac0 \u0a9c\u0ab6\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0ab2\u0ab8\u0acb|date=29 August 2014|publisher=[[Sandesh (Indian newspaper)|Sandesh]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903071820/http://www.sandesh.com/article.aspx?newsid=2980475|archivedate=3 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Times of India]]'' reviewed it positively saying, \"Wonderfully executed, beautifully crafted and crisply edited, the movie makes the popcorn and the hot cuppa more enjoyable.\" and rated it 4 stars out of 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movie-review/Bey-Yaar/articleshow/41451975.cms|title=Bey Yaar|date=1 Sep 2014|author=Navya Malini|publisher=[[Times of India]]}} {{rating|4|5}}</ref> [[Jay Vasavada]] called it, \"Brilliant, Brave, Bright\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/index.php/articles/display_article/anavrut7231|title=Anavrut \u2013 Jay Vasavada|date=3 Sep 2014|publisher=[[Gujarat Samachar]]|author=Jay Vasavada}}</ref> The film was screened at [[New York Indian Film Festival]] on 5 May 2015 and became the first ever Gujarati film to do so.<ref name=\"NIYFF\"/>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film had a limited release across cinemas in [[Gujarat]] and [[Maharashtra]], but was running with packed houses on the day of the release<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=53640&boxid=39410&ed_date=2014-08-30&ed_code=1310009&ed_page=1|title=A full house on Day 1!|date=30 Aug 2014|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]]}}</ref> and continued the success in the first weekend.<ref name=\"BOSuccess\"/> The film completed 100 days in many cities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/ahmedabad/Bey-Yaar-Gujarati-film-Bey-Yaar-celebrates-100-days-in-the-theatre/articleshow/45519929.cms|title=Cast and crew of Bey Yaar celebrate the perfect century|date=15 December 2014|author=Ano Patel}}</ref> and eventually completed 50 weeks.<ref name=\"50 weeks\"/> The film collected {{INRConvert|8.5|c}} on the box office.<ref  name=\"Hindu\"/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n===14th Annual Transmedia Gujarati Screen & Stage Awards===\nThe film was nominated for 14 out of 16 categories and won total 9 awards, including the best film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/Bey-Yaar-gets-nominated-for-14-categories/articleshow/46389430.cms|title=Bey Yaar gets nominated for 14 categories|date=27 February 2015|author=Shruti Jambekar|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/Bey-Yaar-bags-nine-awards/articleshow/46419657.cms|title=Bey Yaar bags nine awards|author=Shruti Jambekar|date=1 March 2015|publisher=[[Times of India]]}}</ref>\n* '''Best film \u2013 Bey Yaar\n* '''Best director \u2013 Abhishek Jain\n* '''Best scriptwriter (Story, Screenplay & Dialogue) \u2013 Bhavesh Mandalia, Niren H Bhatt\n* Best actor (male) \u2013 Divyang Thakkar\n* Best actor (female) \u2013 Samwedna Suwalka\n* '''Best supporting actor (male) \u2013 [[Darshan Jariwala]]\n* Best supporting actor (male) \u2013 Kavin Dave\n* '''Best supporting actor (female) \u2013 Arati Patel\n* '''Best actor in a negative role \u2013 [[Manoj Joshi (actor)|Manoj Joshi]]\n* Best cinematographer \u2013 Pushkar Singh\n* '''Best Editor \u2013 Satchit Puranik,''' '''Nirav Panchal'''\n* '''Best music \u2013 [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n* '''Best singer (male) \u2013 Darshan Raval\n* '''Best lyrics \u2013 Niren H Bhatt\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3590482|Bey Yaar}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes | Bey_Yaar | Bey Yaar }}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Beyyaarthefilm Bey Yaar] on [[Facebook]]\n\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bey_Yaar"}
{"title_page": "Al-Jaish SC (Baghdad)", "text_new": "{{About|the Iraqi football club|other uses|Al-Jaish (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname = Al-Jaish SC |\n  image    = Aljaishiraq.png |\n  fullname = Al-Jaish Sports Club |\n  nickname = |\n  founded  = |\n  ground   = [[Al Jaish Stadium]] |\n  capacity =  6,000 |\n  chairman = |\n  manager  = {{flagicon|IRQ}} Maher Ohkla |\n  league   = [[Iraq Division One]] |\n  season   = [[2015\u201316 Iraq Division One|2015\u201316]]|\n  position = Iraq Division One, 12th|\n  pattern_la1=_whiteborder|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=_whiteborder|\n  leftarm1=FF0000|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FF0000|shorts1=111111|socks1=FF0000|\n  pattern_la2=_redshoulders|pattern_b2=_redshoulders|pattern_ra2=_redshoulders|\n  leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FF0000|socks2=FFFFFF|\n\n}}\n\n'''Nadi Al-Jaish Al-Riyadhi Al-Iraqi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062c\u064a\u0634 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a|lit=''Iraqi Army Sports Club''}}), known as '''Al-Jaish Sports Club''' or simply '''Al-Jaish''' for a short, is an Iraqi football club based in [[Baghdad]].  The team has won the [[Iraqi Premier League]] once in its history, back in 1984.  For the 2008/09 season Al Jaish will play in the [[Iraq Division One]] as they were relegated from the [[Iraqi Premier League]] the season before. They hold the joint-record for the longest whole league season undefeated in Iraq (24 games in 1983/84).\n\n==History==\nThe club was named on past '''Al-Firqa Al-Thalitha'''.\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic===\n====National====\n*'''[[Iraqi Premier League]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1983\u201384 Iraqi National League|1983\u201384]]\n\n*'''[[Iraq FA Cup]] Winners'''\n**'''Winners (2):'''  [[1979\u201380 Iraq FA Cup|1979\u201380]], [[1982\u201383 Iraq FA Cup|1982\u201383]]\n\n====Regional====\n*'''[[Iraqi Central League]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1965\u201366 Iraqi Central Premier League|1965\u201366]]\n\n*'''Iraqi Central Second Division'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1962\n\n*'''[[Iraqi Central Perseverance Cup]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1966 Iraqi Central Perseverance Cup|1966]]\n\n====Friendly====\n*'''Al-Qadsia Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1983\n\n*'''Military Friendship Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1980\n\n*'''Republics Cup'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1966\n\n*'''Army Cup Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1961\n\n===International===\n====Friendly====\n*'''Marah Halim Cup'''\n**'''Winners (1):'''  1984\n\n*'''[[Rovers Cup]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1983\n\n==Famous Head Coaches==\n\n*{{Flagicon|Iraq}} [[Munzir Al-Waaiz]]\n*{{Flagicon|Iraq}} [[Hakeem Shaker]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.goalzz.com/main.aspx?team=1764 Club's page on Goalzz.com]\n\n{{Iraq Division 1}}\n{{Iraq Super League}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Sport in Baghdad]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in Iraq]]\n\n\n{{Iraq-footyclub-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Iraqi football club|other uses|Al-Jaish (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname = Al-Jaish SC |\n  image    = Aljaishiraq.png |\n  fullname = Al-Jaish Sports Club |\n  nickname = |\n  founded  = |\n  ground   = [[Al Jaish Stadium]] |\n  capacity =  6,000 |\n  chairman = |\n  manager  = {{flagicon|IRQ}} Maher Ohkla |\n  league   = [[Iraq Division One]] |\n  season   = [[2015\u201316 Iraq Division One|2015\u201316]]|\n  position = Iraq Division One, 12th|\n  pattern_la1=_whiteborder|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=_whiteborder|\n  leftarm1=FF0000|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FF0000|shorts1=111111|socks1=FF0000|\n  pattern_la2=_redshoulders|pattern_b2=_redshoulders|pattern_ra2=_redshoulders|\n  leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FF0000|socks2=FFFFFF|\n\n}}\n\n'''Nadi Al-Jaish Al-Riyadhi Al-Iraqi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062c\u064a\u0634 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a|lit=''Iraqi Army Sports Club''}}), known as '''Al-Jaish Sports Club''' or simply '''Al-Jaish''' for a short, is an Iraqi football club based in [[Baghdad]].  The team has won the [[Iraqi Premier League]] once in its history, back in 1984.  For the 2008/09 season Al Jaish will play in the [[Iraq Division One]] as they were relegated from the [[Iraqi Premier League]] the season before. They hold the joint-record for the longest whole league season undefeated in Iraq (24 games in 1983/84).\n\n==History==\nThe club was named on past '''Al-Firqa Al-Thalitha'''.\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic===\n====National====\n*'''[[Iraqi Premier League]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1983\u201384 Iraqi National League|1983\u201384]]\n\n*'''[[Iraq FA Cup]] Winners'''\n**'''Winners (2):'''  [[1979\u201380 Iraq FA Cup|1979\u201380]], [[1982\u201383 Iraq FA Cup|1982\u201383]]\n\n====Regional====\n*'''[[Iraqi Central League]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1965\u201366 Iraqi Central Premier League|1965\u201366]]\n\n*'''Iraqi Central Second Division'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1962\n\n*'''[[Iraqi Central Perseverance Cup]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1966 Iraqi Central Perseverance Cup|1966]]\n\n====Friendly====\n*'''Al-Qadsia Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1983\n\n*'''Military Friendship Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1980\n\n*'''Republics Cup'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1966\n\n*'''Army Cup Championship'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1961\n\n===International===\n====Friendly====\n*'''Marah Halim Cup'''\n**'''Winners (1):'''  1984\n\n*'''[[Rovers Cup]]'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1983\n\n==Famous Head Coaches==\n\n*{{Flagicon|Iraq}} [[Munir Al-Waat]]\n*{{Flagicon|Iraq}} [[Hakeem Shaker]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.goalzz.com/main.aspx?team=1764 Club's page on Goalzz.com]\n\n{{Iraq Division 1}}\n{{Iraq Super League}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Sport in Baghdad]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in Iraq]]\n\n\n{{Iraq-footyclub-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Abd Moh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamous Head Coaches", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Jaish_SC_(Baghdad)"}
{"title_page": "Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath", "text_new": "{{short description|20th and 21st-century British businessman and Marquess }}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name = The Marquess of Bath\n|image=Bath, marquess of.svg\n|caption=Arms of the Marquess of Bath: ''Quarterly: 1st and 4th, Barry of ten Or and Sable (Botteville); 2nd and 3rd, Argent, a Lion rampant with tail nowed and erect Gules (Thynne)''\n| honorific-suffix = \n| birth_name = Ceawlin Henry Laszlo Thynn\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|6|6}}\n| alma_mater = [[University College London]]\n| occupation = Businessman\n| office = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n| term_start = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Alexander Thynn]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Emma McQuiston]]|2013}}\n| children = {{Plainlist|\n*John Thynn, Viscount Weymouth\n*Lord Henry Thynn}}\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]]\n*[[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Ceawlin Henry Laszlo Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|u\u02d0|\u0259|l|\u026a|n|}};  {{respell|SOO|\u0259-lin}};<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite news |last1=Kamp |first1=David |title=Meet the Viscountess Transforming the Idea of British Aristocracy |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/viscountess-weymouth-emma-thynn |accessdate=19 March 2019 |work=Vanity Fair |date=25 April 2018}}</ref> born 6 June 1974), styled '''Viscount Weymouth''' between 1992 and 2020, is a British businessman and the first son and second child of the late [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]], and his wife, [[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]].<ref name=\"thisislondon.co.uk\">[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-11369783-the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos.do London Evening Standard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606082958/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-11369783-the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos.do |date=6 June 2011 }}</ref> He is involved in a number of companies in the leisure, tourism, real estate, and financial services sectors.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/ceawlin-thynn/1/69a/aa3|title=Ceawlin Thynn&nbsp;\u2013 LinkedIn|work=linkedin.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCeawlin Thynn attended Horningsham Primary School and [[Kingdown School|Kingdown Comprehensive School]] in [[Warminster]], [[Bedales School]] in [[Hampshire]], and read economics and philosophy at [[University College London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos-7288412.html|title=The viscount who cleaned the loos|date=16 June 2004|work=thisislondon.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Thynn was injured in a building collapse in Paharganj, New Delhi,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/police-baffled-as-delhi-search-reveals-no-trace-of-bomb-1306335.html|title=Police baffled as Delhi search reveals no trace of bomb|date=22 April 1996|work=independent.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> which killed his fianc\u00e9e, Jane Kirby, and his business partner, Crinan Wilde.\n\n==Business==\nThynn began his business career as an emerging markets specialist at the London investment bank [[Caspian Securities]], before becoming a partner in Sabre Projects, a real estate development firm.<ref name=\"thisislondon.co.uk\"/> At Sabre he put together a project with [[Bank Menatep|Group Menatep]], the holding company of Russia's then-largest oil company, [[Yukos]], to develop a mid-market hotel in every major city in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://evetns.moscowtimes.ru/business/article/menatep-to-set-up-300m-hotel-chain/240153.html|title=Moscow Times|work=moscowtimes.ru|accessdate=26 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120711180219/http://evetns.moscowtimes.ru/business/article/menatep-to-set-up-300m-hotel-chain/240153.html|archivedate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotelnewsresource.com/article5274Group_MENATEP_Launches_Hotel_Program_in_Russia_with_Sabre_Projects__Marriott.html|title=Group MENATEP Launches Hotel Program in Russia with Sabre Projects, Marriott|first=Hotel News|last=Resource|work=hotelnewsresource.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Thynn formed The Lion Trust, a [[Private equity fund|private equity vehicle]] of which he is the principal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Heir-gets-Longleat-Cheddar-Gorge/story-12285059-detail/story.html|title=Heir gets lions, the gorge, but not the wardrobe|date=11 March 2010|work=thisissomerset.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026025900/http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Heir-gets-Longleat-Cheddar-Gorge/story-12285059-detail/story.html#|archive-date=26 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Lion Trust invests in a range of mature and emerging markets.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eredene.com/|title=Home&nbsp;\u2013 Eredene Capital PLC|work=eredene.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince June 2010, Thynn has been a director at Finmetron AB, a Swedish listed firm offering [[Factoring (finance)|factoring]] services in Russia.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finmetron.com/|title=Finmetron website|work=finmetron.com|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619184851/http://finmetron.com/|archive-date=19 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markets.ft.com/research/Markets/Tearsheets/Business-profile?s=FINM%20B:STO|title=Storytel AB (publ), STORY B:AKT summary&nbsp;\u2013 FT.com|work=ft.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 until 2013, Thynn was executive chairman of Wombat's Holdings GmbH&nbsp;\u2013 a chain of hostels in Germany and Austria&nbsp;\u2013 having acquired a majority stake in the company.<ref name=\"thesundaytimes.co.uk\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/business/Retail_and_leisure/article671276.ece|title=Longleat heir moves into hostels&nbsp;\u2013 The Sunday Times|work=thesundaytimes.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|date=17 July 2011|last1=Goodman|first1=Matthew}}</ref><ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wombats-hostels.com|title=Wombats Hostels! |work=wombats-hostels.com |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> Wombat's hostels were voted the best in the world by customers of Hostelworld in 2006, 2007, 2008, and 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hostelworld.com/wombats|title=Wombats Hostels, book now with Hostelworld |work=hostelworld.com |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> The company was repurchased by its former owners in 2013, leaving Thynn without any official role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wombats-hostels.com/about-us/legal/|title=Legal&nbsp;\u2013 Wombats Hostels!|work=wombats-hostels.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Longleat==\nIn January 2009, Thynn became chairman of Longleat Enterprises, a limited company which comprises operations at Longleat House and [[Longleat Safari Park|Safari Park]] on the family estate of [[Longleat]], near [[Warminster]] in [[Wiltshire]], as well as the commercial activities at [[Cheddar Gorge]], in the [[Mendip Hills]] in [[Somerset]].<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7060610.ece|title=Login|work=timesonline.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cheddargorge.co.uk/ Cheddar Gorge]</ref> Following [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Lord Bath's]] retirement in 2010, Thynn hired a new chief executive, David Bradley, formerly of [[Legoland]].<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/8469300/Ceawlin-Thynn-interview-It-was-a-different-normality-says-the-young-lion-of-Longleat.html|title=Ceawlin Thynn interview: It was a different normality, says the young lion of Longleat|last=Gerard|first=Jasper|date=22 April 2011|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/whos-king-of-the-leisure-parks-720613.html |title=US|work=independent.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> Together they have worked with designers from Hollywood on improving the house and park; additions to the park include \"Jungle Kingdom\", \"Monkey Temple\", and \"Hunters of the Sky\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/>\n\nIn September 2013, Bradley resigned<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-chief-executive-resigns/story-19935651-detail/story.html|title=Longleat chief executive resigns|date=15 October 2013|work=westerndailypress.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007061409/http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-chief-executive-resigns/story-19935651-detail/story.html#|archive-date=7 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in February 2014 American Bob Montgomery was hired for the role.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Longleat lions welfare criticisms bring new chief executive to safari park|url = http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-moves-end-bad-press-animal-welfare/story-20688486-detail/story.html|accessdate = 6 October 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151007070519/http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-moves-end-bad-press-animal-welfare/story-20688486-detail/story.html#|archive-date = 7 October 2015|url-status=dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThynn is (and [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|his father]] was) a trustee of the Longleat Charitable Trust, a [[registered charity]].<ref>{{EW charity|1057715|Longleat Charitable Trust}}</ref> The trust was established in 1996 and has focused charitable activity on relieving poverty amongst people living around the Longleat Estate and Cheddar Gorge, and supporting local pensioners with their fuel bills. The trust also provides grants to local schools and churches, including the refurbishment of the village hall{{specify|reason=which village?|date=April 2020}}.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn November 2012, aged 38, Thynn announced his engagement to [[Emma Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Emma McQuiston]] (born 1986), daughter of Suzanna McQuiston and Nigerian oil tycoon [[Ladi Jadesimi]], a founder and the executive chairman of [[LADOL|Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics]].<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=44461994&ticker=FCMB:NL&previousCapId=22125422&previousTitle=FIRST%20CITY%20MONUMENT%20BANK%20PLC Ladi Jadesimi], business profile</ref><ref>Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics Base: [http://www.ladol.com/about-us/management Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics Base Management], accessdate: 8 January 2017</ref> Emma is a much younger half-sister of Iain McQuiston (born circa 1962), husband of Lord Bath's aunt, Lady Silvy Cerne Thynne (daughter of Ceawlin's paternal grandfather the 6th Marquess of Bath by his second wife).<ref name=\"vf\"/>\n\nThe couple's 2013 marriage was boycotted by his parents, but attended by his sister.<ref>[https://www.naij.com/543918-british-lord-weds-nigerian-tycoons-daughter-bans-mother-attending-photos.html Racism Toward First Black Marchioness Stirs Rift At Longleat], naij.com, accessdate: 8 January 2017</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2014, the Marchioness, then just known as Viscountess Weymouth, gave birth to their first child, John Alexander Ladi Thynn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/peerage-news/Vkq5YSQiUUU|title=Google Groups|work=google.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>  On 30 December 2016, their second child, Henry Richard Isaac Thynn, was born by [[surrogacy]] at a private clinic in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/209842/thynn|title=THYNN - Births Announcements - Telegraph Announcements|website=announcements.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/07/longleat-heir-has-son-born-surrogacy-first-british-aristocracy/ Longleat heir has son born by surrogacy after medics warned pregnancy could kill Lady Weymouth], telegraph.co.uk, 7 January 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Alexander Thynne]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n | years  = 2020\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current British marquesses}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bath, Thynn, Ceawlin, 8th Marquess of}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Bath]]\n[[Category:British marquesses|Bath]]\n[[Category:British people of Hungarian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|20th and 21st-century British businessman and Marquess }}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name = The Marquess of Bath\n|image=Bath, marquess of.svg\n|caption=Arms of the Marquess of Bath: ''Quarterly: 1st and 4th, Barry of ten Or and Sable (Botteville); 2nd and 3rd, Argent, a Lion rampant with tail nowed and erect Gules (Thynne)''\n| honorific-suffix = \n| birth_name = Ceawlin Henry Laszlo Thynn\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|6|6}}\n| alma_mater = [[University College London]]\n| occupation = Businessman\n| office = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n| term_start = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Alexander Thynn]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Emma McQuiston]]|2013}}\n| children = {{Plainlist|\n*John Thynn, Viscount Weymouth\n*Lord Henry Thynn}}\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]]\n*[[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Ceawlin Henry Laszlo Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|u\u02d0|\u0259|l|\u026a|n|}};  {{respell|SOO|\u0259-lin}};<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite news |last1=Kamp |first1=David |title=Meet the Viscountess Transforming the Idea of British Aristocracy |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/viscountess-weymouth-emma-thynn |accessdate=19 March 2019 |work=Vanity Fair |date=25 April 2018}}</ref> born 6 June 1974), styled '''Viscount Weymouth''' between 1992 and 2020, is a British businessman and the first son and second child of the late [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]], and his wife, [[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]].<ref name=\"thisislondon.co.uk\">[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-11369783-the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos.do London Evening Standard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606082958/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-11369783-the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos.do |date=6 June 2011 }}</ref> He is involved in a number of companies in the leisure, tourism, real estate, and financial services sectors.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/ceawlin-thynn/1/69a/aa3|title=Ceawlin Thynn&nbsp;\u2013 LinkedIn|work=linkedin.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCeawlin Thynn attended Horningsham Primary School and [[Kingdown School|Kingdown Comprehensive School]] in [[Warminster]], [[Bedales School]] in [[Hampshire]], and read economics and philosophy at [[University College London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/the-viscount-who-cleaned-the-loos-7288412.html|title=The viscount who cleaned the loos|date=16 June 2004|work=thisislondon.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Thynn was injured in a building collapse in Paharganj, New Delhi,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/police-baffled-as-delhi-search-reveals-no-trace-of-bomb-1306335.html|title=Police baffled as Delhi search reveals no trace of bomb|date=22 April 1996|work=independent.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> which killed his fianc\u00e9e, Jane Kirby, and his business partner, Crinan Wilde.\n\n==Business==\nThynn began his business career as an emerging markets specialist at the London investment bank [[Caspian Securities]], before becoming a partner in Sabre Projects, a real estate development firm.<ref name=\"thisislondon.co.uk\"/> At Sabre he put together a project with [[Bank Menatep|Group Menatep]], the holding company of Russia's then-largest oil company, [[Yukos]], to develop a mid-market hotel in every major city in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://evetns.moscowtimes.ru/business/article/menatep-to-set-up-300m-hotel-chain/240153.html|title=Moscow Times|work=moscowtimes.ru|accessdate=26 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120711180219/http://evetns.moscowtimes.ru/business/article/menatep-to-set-up-300m-hotel-chain/240153.html|archivedate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotelnewsresource.com/article5274Group_MENATEP_Launches_Hotel_Program_in_Russia_with_Sabre_Projects__Marriott.html|title=Group MENATEP Launches Hotel Program in Russia with Sabre Projects, Marriott|first=Hotel News|last=Resource|work=hotelnewsresource.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Thynn formed The Lion Trust, a [[Private equity fund|private equity vehicle]] of which he is the principal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Heir-gets-Longleat-Cheddar-Gorge/story-12285059-detail/story.html|title=Heir gets lions, the gorge, but not the wardrobe|date=11 March 2010|work=thisissomerset.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026025900/http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Heir-gets-Longleat-Cheddar-Gorge/story-12285059-detail/story.html#|archive-date=26 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Lion Trust invests in a range of mature and emerging markets.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eredene.com/|title=Home&nbsp;\u2013 Eredene Capital PLC|work=eredene.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince June 2010, Thynn has been a director at Finmetron AB, a Swedish listed firm offering [[Factoring (finance)|factoring]] services in Russia.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finmetron.com/|title=Finmetron website|work=finmetron.com|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619184851/http://finmetron.com/|archive-date=19 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markets.ft.com/research/Markets/Tearsheets/Business-profile?s=FINM%20B:STO|title=Storytel AB (publ), STORY B:AKT summary&nbsp;\u2013 FT.com|work=ft.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 until 2013, Thynn was executive chairman of Wombat's Holdings GmbH&nbsp;\u2013 a chain of hostels in Germany and Austria&nbsp;\u2013 having acquired a majority stake in the company.<ref name=\"thesundaytimes.co.uk\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/business/Retail_and_leisure/article671276.ece|title=Longleat heir moves into hostels&nbsp;\u2013 The Sunday Times|work=thesundaytimes.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|date=17 July 2011|last1=Goodman|first1=Matthew}}</ref><ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wombats-hostels.com|title=Wombats Hostels! |work=wombats-hostels.com |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> Wombat's hostels were voted the best in the world by customers of Hostelworld in 2006, 2007, 2008, and 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hostelworld.com/wombats|title=Wombats Hostels, book now with Hostelworld |work=hostelworld.com |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> The company was repurchased by its former owners in 2013, leaving Thynn without any official role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wombats-hostels.com/about-us/legal/|title=Legal&nbsp;\u2013 Wombats Hostels!|work=wombats-hostels.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Longleat==\nIn January 2009, Thynn became chairman of Longleat Enterprises, a limited company which comprises operations at Longleat House and [[Longleat Safari Park|Safari Park]] on the family estate of [[Longleat]], near [[Warminster]] in [[Wiltshire]], as well as the commercial activities at [[Cheddar Gorge]], in the [[Mendip Hills]] in [[Somerset]].<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7060610.ece|title=Login|work=timesonline.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cheddargorge.co.uk/ Cheddar Gorge]</ref> Following [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Lord Bath's]] retirement in 2010, Thynn hired a new chief executive, David Bradley, formerly of [[Legoland]].<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/8469300/Ceawlin-Thynn-interview-It-was-a-different-normality-says-the-young-lion-of-Longleat.html|title=Ceawlin Thynn interview: It was a different normality, says the young lion of Longleat|last=Gerard|first=Jasper|date=22 April 2011|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/whos-king-of-the-leisure-parks-720613.html |title=US|work=independent.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> Together they have worked with designers from Hollywood on improving the house and park; additions to the park include \"Jungle Kingdom\", \"Monkey Temple\", and \"Hunters of the Sky\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/>\n\nIn September 2013, Bradley resigned<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-chief-executive-resigns/story-19935651-detail/story.html|title=Longleat chief executive resigns|date=15 October 2013|work=westerndailypress.co.uk|accessdate=26 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007061409/http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-chief-executive-resigns/story-19935651-detail/story.html#|archive-date=7 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in February 2014 American Bob Montgomery was hired for the role.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Longleat lions welfare criticisms bring new chief executive to safari park|url = http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-moves-end-bad-press-animal-welfare/story-20688486-detail/story.html|accessdate = 6 October 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151007070519/http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Longleat-moves-end-bad-press-animal-welfare/story-20688486-detail/story.html#|archive-date = 7 October 2015|url-status=dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThynn is (and [[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|his father]] was) a trustee of the Longleat Charitable Trust, a [[registered charity]].<ref>{{EW charity|1057715|Longleat Charitable Trust}}</ref> The trust was established in 1996 and has focused charitable activity on relieving poverty amongst people living around the Longleat Estate and Cheddar Gorge, and supporting local pensioners with their fuel bills. The trust also provides grants to local schools and churches, including the refurbishment of the village hall{{specify|reason=which village?|date=April 2020}}.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn November 2012, aged 38, Thynn announced his engagement to [[Emma Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Emma McQuiston]] (born 1986), daughter of Suzanna McQuiston and Nigerian oil tycoon [[Ladi Jadesimi]], a founder and the executive chairman of [[LADOL|Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics]].<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=44461994&ticker=FCMB:NL&previousCapId=22125422&previousTitle=FIRST%20CITY%20MONUMENT%20BANK%20PLC Ladi Jadesimi], business profile</ref><ref>Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics Base: [http://www.ladol.com/about-us/management Lagos Deep Offshore Logistics Base Management], accessdate: 8 January 2017</ref> Emma is a much younger half-sister of Iain McQuiston (born circa 1962), husband of Lord Bath's aunt, Lady Silvy Cerne Thynne (daughter of Ceawlin's paternal grandfather the 6th Marquess of Bath by his second wife).<ref name=\"vf\"/>\n\nThe couple's 2013 marriage was boycotted by his parents, but attended by his sister.<ref>[https://www.naij.com/543918-british-lord-weds-nigerian-tycoons-daughter-bans-mother-attending-photos.html Racism Toward First Black Marchioness Stirs Rift At Longleat], naij.com, accessdate: 8 January 2017</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2014, the Marchioness, then just known as Viscountess Weymouth, gave birth to their first child, John Alexander Ladi Thynn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/peerage-news/Vkq5YSQiUUU|title=Google Groups|work=google.com|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>  On 30 December 2016, their second child, Henry Richard Isaac Thynn, was born by [[surrogacy]] at a private clinic in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/209842/thynn|title=THYNN - Births Announcements - Telegraph Announcements|website=announcements.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/07/longleat-heir-has-son-born-surrogacy-first-british-aristocracy/ Longleat heir has son born by surrogacy after medics warned pregnancy could kill Lady Weymouth], telegraph.co.uk, 7 January 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath|Alexander Thynne]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n | years  = 2020 -\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current British marquesses}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bath, Thynn, Ceawlin, 8th Marquess of}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Bath]]\n[[Category:British marquesses|Bath]]\n[[Category:British people of Hungarian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Editor FIN", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceawlin_Thynn,_8th_Marquess_of_Bath"}
{"title_page": "Comstock Northwest, Michigan", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Comstock Northwest, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Census-designated place]] (CDP) & [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Kalamazoo_County_Michigan_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Comstock_Northwest_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Comstock Northwest, Michigan\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in Michigan|Townships]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Comstock Township, Michigan|Comstock]], [[Kalamazoo Township, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 8.24\n|area_land_km2            = 8.20\n|area_water_km2           = 0.04\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 5455\n|population_density_km2   = 665.3\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 870\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|19|23|N|85|31|19|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-17690<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 2393384<ref>{{gnis|2393384}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Comstock Northwest''' is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan|Kalamazoo County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. As a CDP, it is not a municipality. The population was 5,455 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617690| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Comstock Northwest CDP, Michigan| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=March 14, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213052345/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617690| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> up from 4,472 at the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe CDP is in the northwest portion of [[Comstock Township, Michigan|Comstock Charter Township]], just northeast of [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]. It also includes a small sliver of land in northeast [[Kalamazoo Township, Michigan|Kalamazoo Charter Township]] between the city of Kalamazoo and Comstock Charter Township. The CDP is bordered to the west by Kalamazoo and to the southwest by unincorporated [[Eastwood, Michigan|Eastwood]].\n\n[[M-343 (Michigan highway)|M-343]] is the main highway through the community. It leads southwest {{convert|4|mi|0}} to the center of Kalamazoo and northeast {{convert|5|mi|0}} to [[Richland, Michigan|Richland]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the Comstock Northwest CDP has a total area of {{convert|8.2|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|0.04|sqkm|order=flip|2}}, or 0.54%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 4,472 people, 1,965 households, and 1,208 families residing in the CDP.  The [[population density]] was 1,404.3 per square mile (543.0/km\u00b2).  There were 2,079 housing units at an average density of 652.9 per square mile (252.4/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the CDP was 87.81% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 7.51% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.27% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.65% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.96% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.79% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.10% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,965 households out of which 28.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 38.5% were non-families. 32.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.27 and the average family size was 2.88.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 23.9% under the age of 18, 10.1% from 18 to 24, 30.4% from 25 to 44, 20.8% from 45 to 64, and 14.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $43,590, and the median income for a family was $56,115. Males had a median income of $41,698 versus $31,713 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $23,961.  About 5.3% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 9.0% of those under age 18 and 3.4% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kalamazoo County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Kalamazoo\u2013Portage metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Comstock Northwest, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Census-designated place]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Kalamazoo_County_Michigan_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Comstock_Northwest_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Comstock Northwest, Michigan\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in Michigan|Townships]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Comstock Township, Michigan|Comstock]], [[Kalamazoo Township, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 8.24\n|area_land_km2            = 8.20\n|area_water_km2           = 0.04\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 5455\n|population_density_km2   = 665.3\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 870\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|19|23|N|85|31|19|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-17690<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 2393384<ref>{{gnis|2393384}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Comstock Northwest''' is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan|Kalamazoo County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. As a CDP, it is not a municipality. The population was 5,455 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617690| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Comstock Northwest CDP, Michigan| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=March 14, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213052345/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2617690| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> up from 4,472 at the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe CDP is in the northwest portion of [[Comstock Township, Michigan|Comstock Charter Township]], just northeast of [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]. It also includes a small sliver of land in northeast [[Kalamazoo Township, Michigan|Kalamazoo Charter Township]] between the city of Kalamazoo and Comstock Charter Township. The CDP is bordered to the west by Kalamazoo and to the southwest by unincorporated [[Eastwood, Michigan|Eastwood]].\n\n[[M-343 (Michigan highway)|M-343]] is the main highway through the community. It leads southwest {{convert|4|mi|0}} to the center of Kalamazoo and northeast {{convert|5|mi|0}} to [[Richland, Michigan|Richland]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the Comstock Northwest CDP has a total area of {{convert|8.2|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|0.04|sqkm|order=flip|2}}, or 0.54%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 4,472 people, 1,965 households, and 1,208 families residing in the CDP.  The [[population density]] was 1,404.3 per square mile (543.0/km\u00b2).  There were 2,079 housing units at an average density of 652.9 per square mile (252.4/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the CDP was 87.81% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 7.51% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.27% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.65% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.96% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.79% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.10% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,965 households out of which 28.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 38.5% were non-families. 32.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.27 and the average family size was 2.88.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 23.9% under the age of 18, 10.1% from 18 to 24, 30.4% from 25 to 44, 20.8% from 45 to 64, and 14.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $43,590, and the median income for a family was $56,115. Males had a median income of $41,698 versus $31,713 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $23,961.  About 5.3% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 9.0% of those under age 18 and 3.4% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kalamazoo County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Kalamazoo\u2013Portage metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comstock_Northwest,_Michigan"}
